.ddx/executions/20260512T023608-03dd1cd6/manifest.json:14:    "description": "PROBLEM\n  After sister bead ddx-1f774edf removes network I/O from Land(), the\n  drain becomes safe for external parallelism (multiple ddx work --once\n  shells running concurrently). However, parallel workers will land their\n  own bead's worktree against the same local main and may produce\n  overlapping changes — multi-worker conflict frequency on Land()'s\n  git merge step is unmeasured. The 2026-05-09 plan-review opus\n  self-review identified this as a key risk: under high parallelism,\n  preservation (resource_exhausted to iteration ref) could become the\n  common path rather than the exception, defeating the gain.\n\n  This bead adds chaos coverage for the parallel-landing case and a\n  sentinel that fails if the preservation rate exceeds an acceptable\n  threshold under simulated load.\n\nCURRENT STATE\n  - cli/internal/bead/chaos_test.go and chaos2_test.go cover\n    bead.Store-layer concurrency only.\n  - cli/internal/agent/tracker_lock_test.go covers single-worker\n    semantics.\n  - Sister bead ddx-c019e48a covers stale-lock recovery for a single\n    worker's local-only land. It does not cover N\u003e1 workers landing in\n    parallel.\n  - No test verifies what happens when worker A lands branch-A into\n    main, then worker B (whose worktree was branched from pre-A main)\n    tries to land branch-B with overlapping changes.\n\nPROPOSED FIX\n  Add three chaos tests in cli/internal/agent/landing_chaos_test.go (new\n  file, or extend tracker_lock_test.go):\n\n  1. TestConcurrentLand_NonOverlappingChanges_BothLandClean:\n     - Spawn 3 worker goroutines, each with its own bead/worktree\n       touching disjoint files.\n     - All three call Land() concurrently.\n     - Assert: all three land on local main, in some order; no\n       preservation; main contains all three commits.\n\n  2. TestConcurrentLand_OverlappingChanges_OneLandsRestPreserve:\n     - Spawn 3 worker goroutines, each touching the same file with\n       different content.\n     - All three call Land() concurrently.\n     - Assert: exactly one lands; the other two are preserved to\n       iteration refs; the preserved branches are intact and contain\n       their bead's full work.\n\n  3. TestConcurrentLand_PreservationRateUnderLoadIsBounded:\n     - Spawn N worker goroutines (N=4) over M cycles (M=10), each with\n       a randomized mix of overlapping/non-overlapping changes.\n     - Assert: preservation rate is \u003c 50% (i.e., at least half of\n       attempts land cleanly). This is a smoke check that parallel\n       drain is viable, not a hard SLA.\n\n  Use deterministic timing (channels or synctest), not wall-clock.\n  Use testutils.NewFixtureRepo or t.TempDir() per test.\n  Depends on sister bead ddx-1f774edf so the lock holds are sub-second\n  (otherwise the test exercises today's contention bug, not the\n  parallel-landing concern).\n\nNON-SCOPE\n  - Multi-process chaos (these are goroutine-level concurrent landings\n    using fake LandingGitOps that mirror the real merge logic).\n  - Coordinating workers via a \"land queue\" abstraction (separate\n    architectural concern; this bead establishes the baseline measurement\n    against which any such work would be evaluated).\n\nINTERSECTIONS\n  - Sister bead ddx-1f774edf (depends on it landing first).\n  - Sister bead (just-filed) \"agent/lock: instrument bead.Store\n    WithLock wait time\" — its metrics are referenced by these tests'\n    assertions if available.\n  - Sister bead ddx-c019e48a complements this for the single-worker\n    stale-lock case.",
