.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:220:{"acceptance":"AC1. ProviderTimeout is configurable per-project via .ddx/config.yaml under agent.routing or agent.endpoints — e.g. agent.endpoints[provider].request_timeout_seconds — and the current 15-minute hardcoded constant becomes a default that can be overridden upward (or removed entirely) per provider.\n\nAC2. ProviderTimeout is configurable per-tier via the model-overrides path: cheap tier on a known thinking model (qwen3.6, deepseek-r1, etc.) defaults to a longer cap (e.g. 60 min or unlimited). Cloud chat models keep the 15-min default.\n\nAC3. The idle-read timeout (DefaultProviderIdleReadTimeout = 5 min) is the primary stalled-TCP-socket defense; documentation in cli/internal/agent/serviceconfig.go and the user-facing config docs explain the relationship between idle-read and wall-clock-request timeouts and when each fires.\n\nAC4. When ProviderTimeout fires, the error message names the exact timeout setting and the path to override it (e.g. 'request_timeout=15m exceeded; configure agent.endpoints.\u003cname\u003e.request_timeout_seconds in .ddx/config.yaml').\n\nAC5. execute-loop / execute-bead --request-timeout DURATION CLI flag exists for one-off overrides during debugging.\n\nAC6. Default for known-thinking-model surfaces (provider.type=lmstudio AND model name matches qwen3.6/qwen-r1/deepseek-r1 etc., or some other declared 'thinking' attribute) is bumped to a sensible value (e.g. 60 min) without requiring per-project config.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-04-29T20:58:18Z","claimed-machine":"eitri","claimed-pid":"932496","closing_commit_sha":"99375eaf330ea13838d40d2176d193ae3cd3453b","created_at":"2026-04-29T18:50:46.475563514Z","description":"Source: cli/internal/agent/serviceconfig.go:30\n  const DefaultProviderRequestTimeout = 15 * time.Minute\n\nThis is hardcoded, not surfaced through .ddx/config.yaml or any flag, and is applied uniformly to every provider regardless of model class. It is set on every service path:\n  - cli/internal/agent/agent_runner_service.go:116  ProviderTimeout: DefaultProviderRequestTimeout\n  - cli/internal/agent/service_run.go:153           ProviderTimeout: DefaultProviderRequestTimeout\n\nThe comment justifies it as 'Defeats RC4 of ddx-0a651925: a stalled TCP socket that has delivered headers but stopped emitting body bytes would otherwise pin a goroutine until the outer wall-clock (3h) frees it.'\n\nBut that scenario is already handled by a separate idle-read timeout immediately below, on line 34:\n  const DefaultProviderIdleReadTimeout = 5 * time.Minute\n\nThe 5-minute idle-read timeout is exactly the right tool for the stalled-TCP-socket case (no body bytes for 5 min → fail). The 15-minute wall-clock cap on a single request is the WRONG tool — it kills any legitimately long single Chat call regardless of streaming health.\n\nConcrete impact observed today (2026-04-29 axon repo):\n\n1. axon-db7a6d0a worker (qwen3.6-35b-a3b on bragi via lmstudio)\n   - status: no_changes\n   - duration_ms: 1,762,081 (29 min total — one timeout + retry)\n   - log: 'WARN provider error, retrying attempt=1 err=\"provider request timeout: wall-clock 15m0s\" delay=1s'\n   - Retry consumed another full 15 min, also timed out, no commits produced.\n\n2. axon-80979cb8 + axon-db7a6d0a + axon-ab2e52e0 (3-worker cascade re-launch)\n   - All 3 hit 'provider request timeout: wall-clock 15m0s' on the first attempt\n   - User killed the run before retries could waste another 15 min × 3 each\n\nWhy thinking models hit this:\nqwen3.6-35b-a3b and similar 'thinking' / chain-of-thought reasoning models can spend 5–10+ minutes generating reasoning tokens before producing the first body delta the harness considers progress. Streaming output IS happening (so the idle-read timeout would NOT fire), but the harness is counting wall-clock against the entire request. A single hard problem can blow the 15-minute cap legitimately.\n\nWhy arbitrary timeouts are not helping:\n\na) Same value for cloud providers (claude, codex) and local providers (lmstudio, omlx). Local thinking models routinely need \u003e15 min on hard prompts; claude rarely does. Same cap is wrong for both classes.\n\nb) No way to opt out of the cap per provider, per model, per request, per project. /home/erik/Projects/axon/.ddx/config.yaml has no knob.\n\nc) Retries inherit the same cap. A timeout-prone session retries with the same fate. Burns cycles and tokens.\n\nd) The cap defeats the cascade: when a cheap-tier qwen times out, escalation to standard claude is intended — but on a thinking model the timeout doesn't mean 'broken provider', it means 'this prompt is hard'. We then escalate after wasting 15 min, and the standard tier solves the problem in 2. Net effect of cheap-tier-first becomes negative.","events_attachment":"ddx-2c63bb95/events.jsonl","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-04-29T21:15:18.844737462Z","id":"ddx-2c63bb95","issue_type":"bug","labels":["area:agent","area:routing","area:harness","kind:design-flaw"],"owner":"erik","priority":1,"session_id":"eb-2db5279a","status":"closed","title":"agent: hardcoded 15-minute DefaultProviderRequestTimeout kills thinking-model requests; not configurable","updated_at":"2026-04-29T21:16:13.255743379Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:221:{"acceptance":"**User story:** As an operator, I expect the Sessions page to reflect reality — if I ran `ddx work` today, today's sessions appear within seconds. And I expect the feed not to silently break again the next time the agent execution path is refactored.\n\n**Acceptance criteria:**\n\n1. **Session-index source of truth.** A single writer (invoked from `service.Execute` or a thin wrapper that every production agent-execution path calls) appends one line per completed agent invocation to `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions.index.jsonl`. Fields are pointer-only: id, projectID, beadID, harness, surface, model, startedAt, endedAt, durationMs, cost, tokens, outcome, exitCode, bundlePath (relative), nativeLogRef (relative). No prompt or response bodies embedded.\n\n2. **Single-call-site guarantee.** Unit test enumerates every production code path that executes an agent (execute-bead, execute-loop, `ddx agent run`, quorum, replay if still present) and asserts each appends exactly one index row. If a new path is added later without wiring this up, the test fails.\n\n3. **Visibility restored.** GraphQL `sessions` query reads `sessions.index.jsonl`. Running `ddx work` (or any agent-execution path) against a fixture project causes the new session to appear in a GraphQL query within 2 seconds of completion. E2E test demonstrates this.\n\n4. **Body lazy-load.** A new resolver `session(id: ID!) { prompt response stderr }` loads the heavy fields on demand from the execution bundle (`.ddx/executions/\u003cts\u003e-\u003chash\u003e/`) or the agent-log path, without reading every session in the index.\n\n5. **Legacy migration.** A one-shot command (e.g. `ddx agent log reindex`) seeds the index from the existing `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions.jsonl` (397 MB corpus on the current repo), preserving historical sessions. Integration test uses a fixture `sessions.jsonl` and asserts the index has one row per legacy entry with all pointer fields populated.\n\n6. **Deprecated-file behavior.** After migration, the legacy `sessions.jsonl` is not read by the server. `ddx agent usage` and related CLI commands (`cli/cmd/agent_usage.go:197,246,348`, `cli/cmd/status.go:179`) are updated to read from the index too, verified by their existing tests.\n\n7. **Perf sanity.** The GraphQL `sessions` list resolves in ≤100ms p95 on a fixture with 10,000 index entries; current behavior times out or OOMs. Benchmark captured in bead notes as baseline + after-fix.\n\n8. **UI note.** If there is a gap in the index (e.g. the 2026-04-19 → 2026-04-22 gap on the current repo, assuming backfill from executions/agent-logs is not feasible), the Sessions page surfaces a single-line banner \"No sessions recorded between X and Y\" so the gap is not silently invisible. If backfill is feasible, do it instead and skip the banner.\n\n9. **Playwright e2e.**\n   - Seeds a fixture project with `.ddx/executions/` bundles from both before and after a simulated gap.\n   - Runs the migration command.\n   - Opens `/sessions`, asserts the most recent session timestamp matches the latest bundle, asserts a clicked row lazy-loads prompt/response from the bundle rather than from an embedded payload.\n   - Asserts the feed updates live (within 2s) after a new simulated session is written.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"d733f7f20828708c5179f0ceff9462eaa34654eb","created_at":"2026-04-22T20:22:41.990684692Z","description":"## Observed\n\nThe Sessions page at `/nodes/.../projects/.../sessions` shows nothing newer than **2026-04-19**, three days ago. ddx is definitely still running — `.ddx/executions/` contains bundles from 2026-04-22 (today), `agent-s-*.jsonl` from 2026-04-21, `agent-loop-*.jsonl` from 2026-04-20. The UI simply cannot see them.\n\n## Root cause\n\nThe Sessions GraphQL resolver reads exclusively from `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions.jsonl` (`cli/internal/server/state_graphql.go:504-516`). That file stopped being appended on 2026-04-19 19:46.\n\nThe only writer is `Runner.logSession` (`cli/internal/agent/runner.go:847-914`). It is called from four sites today:\n\n- `cli/internal/agent/runner.go:229` (Runner.Run — legacy)\n- `cli/internal/agent/agent_runner_service.go:216`\n- `cli/internal/agent/claude_stream.go:516`\n- `cli/internal/agent/virtual.go:206`\n\nProduction execute-bead / execute-loop no longer goes through any of them. The Runner-to-service refactor series (`5b933103`, `280f58e0`, `74eceda9`, `7cc1eb58`, `e05c785e`, `9f79f037`) routed the common path through `service.Execute` directly and did not carry forward the sessions.jsonl append. The last sessions.jsonl write lines up with the day that refactor set became default.\n\n## Secondary issue (same fix should address)\n\n`sessions.jsonl` is 397 MB for only 895 entries because each entry embeds the full `result.Output` (see `SessionEntry.Response` at `runner.go:879`). Growth is unbounded, there is no rotation, and `GetAgentSessionsGraphQL` (`state_graphql.go:476-490`) reads the whole file, parses every entry, and sorts in memory on every query. Even if we just restore the writer, the feed is fragile and will become a perf problem again quickly — relevant to `ddx-ad0db8fd` (bead detail was also O(N) scan).\n\n## Proposed direction\n\nDo not simply paper over by re-plumbing `logSession` into `service.Execute`. The right fix is:\n\n1. **Decide the source of truth for \"a session\".** Current candidates on disk:\n   - `.ddx/executions/\u003cts\u003e-\u003chash\u003e/{manifest.json,prompt.md,result.json}` — already written per execute-bead attempt.\n   - `.ddx/agent-logs/agent-*.jsonl` and `agent-s-*.jsonl` — per-run streams from the agent harness.\n   - Bead evidence events (kind:cost already written per attempt, see `execute_bead.go:492`).\n   A session record should be derivable from a combination of execution bundles + agent-log streams, not from a separately-appended aggregate. The aggregate should be an **index**, not a **copy**.\n\n2. **Introduce a lightweight index.** A thin `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions.index.jsonl` containing `{id, projectID, beadID, harness, model, startedAt, endedAt, durationMs, cost, tokens, outcome, bundlePath}` — pointer fields only, no embedded response bodies. Existing `sessions.jsonl` is deprecated to a read-only legacy file during a grace period.\n\n3. **Write the index from `service.Execute`** (or a wrapper the execute-bead / run / execute-loop paths all share). One place to touch. Unit test guards that every production code path that executes an agent appends exactly one index row.\n\n4. **GraphQL reads the index, streams bodies on demand.** `sessions { edges { node { ... } } }` reads the index. A new `session(id: ID!) { prompt, response, stderr }` lazy-loads the heavy fields from the execution bundle or agent-log file when the user expands a row.\n\n5. **Legacy sessions.jsonl compatibility.** The index can be seeded once from the existing 397 MB file so historical data is not lost, then the old file is not read again. One-shot migration command (`ddx agent log reindex` or similar).\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- Replaying or regenerating sessions for the 2026-04-19 → 2026-04-22 gap. If the evidence exists in executions/agent-logs we can backfill the index; if not, accept the gap and cap it with a dated marker in the UI.\n- A full telemetry rework. This bead just restores visibility and fixes the shape.","events_attachment":"ddx-2ceb02fa/events.jsonl","execute-loop-last-detail":"escalation exhausted: unsupported model \"minimax/minimax-m2.7\" for harness \"gemini\"; supported models: gemini-2.5-pro, gemini-2.5-flash, gemini-2.5-flash-lite","execute-loop-last-status":"execution_failed","execute-loop-no-changes-count":1,"feature":"FEAT-010","id":"ddx-2ceb02fa","issue_type":"bug","labels":["feat-008","feat-010","feat-006","perf","observability"],"notes":"## 2026-04-22 — User-directed amendment: shard the index\n\nPer user feedback: a single `sessions.index.jsonl` just replays the same problem at smaller scale. The aggregate needs to be split.\n\n### Revised storage shape\n\n- Directory: `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions/` (per-project, under each registered project's `.ddx`).\n- Inside: **monthly shards** named `sessions-YYYY-MM.jsonl`.\n- Each shard is pointer-only, same fields as the previously-proposed index (id, projectID, beadID, harness, surface, model, startedAt, endedAt, durationMs, cost, tokens, outcome, exitCode, bundlePath, nativeLogRef).\n- Writer resolves the target shard from `time.Now().UTC()` at append time and creates the shard file lazily on first write of the month.\n- Heavy bodies (prompt, response, stderr) stay where they already live — `.ddx/executions/\u003cts\u003e-\u003chash\u003e/` and agent-log streams — and are lazy-loaded by the `session(id:)` resolver.\n\n### Why monthly, not daily / size-based / SQLite\n\n- **Daily** — produces tens of thousands of files over the project lifetime; ReadDir becomes the cost.\n- **Size-based** — requires coordinating rotation with the append; race-prone and hard to test.\n- **SQLite** — overkill for first pass; revisit if a single monthly shard grows past tens of MB.\n- **Monthly** — ≤12 shards/year, human-readable filenames, date-range queries map trivially to shard selection, bounded shard size in practice.\n\n### Reader behavior\n\n- Default Sessions query loads the **current + previous shard** (covers \"recent activity\" for any current date).\n- Date-range queries map the range to a shard set and read only those.\n- Pagination beyond the default window triggers older-shard loads on demand.\n- No shard-coordination lock needed: each month's file is append-only and only the current-month shard is actively written.\n\n### Legacy migration\n\n- `ddx agent log reindex` reads the existing `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions.jsonl` once and splits by each entry's `timestamp` field into the appropriate monthly shards under `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions/`.\n- After migration, the legacy file is renamed `sessions.jsonl.legacy` (not deleted) and never read again by the server. Hand-removal is the user's call.\n- Idempotent: re-running the command merges without duplicating (index row dedup by `id`).\n\n### Revised acceptance criteria (supersedes criteria 1, 5, 6, 7 on original description)\n\n1. **Sharded index writer.** Single shared call site (from `service.Execute` or equivalent wrapper) appends one line to `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions/sessions-YYYY-MM.jsonl`, computing the shard from `time.Now().UTC()`. Test: write across a simulated month boundary and assert two shards exist with the correct split.\n\n5. **Legacy migration shards too.** `ddx agent log reindex` splits `sessions.jsonl` into monthly shards by entry timestamp. Integration test uses a fixture with entries across 3 distinct months and asserts 3 shards are produced with correct contents and no duplicates on re-run.\n\n6. **Server reads the shard directory.** `GetAgentSessionsGraphQL` reads `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions/*.jsonl`, respects any date-range arg, and loads only the shards that intersect the range. Unit test seeds 6 monthly shards and asserts a 2-month query reads exactly 2 files.\n\n7. **Perf on sharded index.** Default Sessions view (current + previous shard) resolves in ≤50ms p95 on a fixture with 12 monthly shards × 10k entries each (120k total). Capture baseline (single-file read of same corpus) vs sharded in bead notes.\n\n(Criteria 2, 3, 4, 8, 9 from the original acceptance list remain as written.)\n\n### Scope clarifier\n\nThis amendment does not change the single-call-site writer guarantee or the lazy-body resolver — those remain the load-bearing ideas. The amendment is specifically about **how the pointer index is physically stored**.\n## 2026-04-23 — Implementation benchmark and evidence\n\nBaseline: `go test ./internal/agent -run '^$' -bench 'Benchmark(ReadSessionIndexDefaultWindow|LegacySessionsJSONLFullScan)$' -benchtime=1x` measured legacy single-file full scan/sort of 120k legacy-shaped rows with 2KB embedded responses at `BenchmarkLegacySessionsJSONLFullScan-12 1 1731705957 ns/op`.\n\nAfter fix: the same command measured the sharded default-window reader at `BenchmarkReadSessionIndexDefaultWindow-12 1 8103661 ns/op` for 12 monthly shards x 10k rows each (120k total), with the default query reading only the current + previous shard window. Environment footer: linux/arm64, Go go1.26.2.\n\nAcceptance evidence: `TestSessionIndexWritesMonthlyShards`, `TestSessionIndexShardFilesSelectsOnlyIntersectingDateRange`, `TestReindexLegacySessionsSplitsShardsAndDedupes`, `TestRunViaServiceWithAppendsOneSessionIndexRow`, `TestProductionAgentExecutionPathsUseIndexedServiceWriter`, `TestGraphQLAgentSessions`, `TestAgentLogReindexMigratesLegacyFile`, existing agent usage/status/processmetrics tests, and `e2e/sessions.spec.ts` cover writer sharding, bounded reads, migration, lazy body loading, deprecated-file read removal, UI gap banner, and live refresh.\n\nREVIEW:BLOCK\n\nMissing session index writer: no changes to `service.Execute`, shared execution wrappers, or agent execution paths to append `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions.index.jsonl`.\nMissing GraphQL changes: no update to `cli/internal/server/state_graphql.go` for index-backed `sessions` or lazy `session(id:)` body loading.\nMissing migration command: no `ddx agent log reindex` or equivalent CLI implementation and no fixture-based migration test.\nMissing CLI usage/status updates: no changes to `cli/cmd/agent_usage.go` or `cli/cmd/status.go` to stop reading legacy `sessions.jsonl`.\nMissing performance validation: no benchmark or fixture proving 10,000 index entries resolve within the required threshold.\nMissing UI gap/banner behavior and Playwright coverage for `/sessions`, lazy loading, migration, and live feed updates.\n\nREVIEW:BLOCK\n\n**AC 1–3**: No `sessions.index.jsonl` schema, writer in `service.Execute`, or updated GraphQL resolver in `cli/internal/server/state_graphql.go`.\n**AC 4**: No `session(id: ID!)` resolver for lazy-loading prompt/response/stderr from execution bundles.\n**AC 5**: No `ddx agent log reindex` command or migration logic.\n**AC 6**: `cli/cmd/agent_usage.go` and `cli/cmd/status.go` are untouched.\n**AC 7**: No benchmark captured.\n**AC 8–9**: No frontend changes or Playwright tests.\n\nREVIEW:BLOCK\n\nMissing `service.Execute` or shared agent-execution wrapper change to append one pointer-only row to `.ddx/agent-logs/sessions.index.jsonl`.\nMissing unit test proving execute-bead, execute-loop, `ddx agent run`, quorum, and replay paths append exactly one index row.\nMissing `cli/internal/server/state_graphql.go` update so GraphQL `sessions` reads `sessions.index.jsonl`.\nMissing new GraphQL `session(id: ID!)` resolver for lazy-loading prompt, response, and stderr from execution bundles or native logs.\nMissing `ddx agent log reindex` or equivalent migration command, plus integration test for legacy `sessions.jsonl`.\nMissing updates to `cli/cmd/agent_usage.go` and `cli/cmd/status.go` to stop reading legacy `sessions.jsonl`.\nMissing 10,000-entry GraphQL sessions benchmark and recorded baseline/after-fix bead notes.\nMissing Sessions UI gap banner or feasible backfill behavior.\nMissing Playwright e2e covering migration, latest timestamp visibility, lazy body load, and live feed updates.","priority":1,"session_id":"eb-b9f50300","status":"closed","title":"Sessions UI is blind to post-2026-04-19 activity: service.Execute path no longer writes sessions.jsonl","updated_at":"2026-04-23T04:18:24.247572547Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:229:{"acceptance":"ddx agent execute-loop --harness claude --model claude-sonnet-4-6 invokes the claude binary, not ddx-agent; session log shows model: claude-sonnet-4-6 not model: vidar or model: bragi; if --model specifies an unrecognized claude model, the error is surfaced before any bead is claimed; ddx agent execute-loop --harness agent --model vidar continues to work as before (regression guard)","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-04-14T07:45:16Z","claimed-machine":"eitri","claimed-pid":"1412283","closing_commit_sha":"e0f5fca79640c9ba54c8ef27113597e7e4dfaeaa","created_at":"2026-04-13T20:50:15.374772587Z","description":"When execute-loop is invoked with both --harness claude and --model \u003cprovider-name\u003e (e.g. --model claude-sonnet-4-6), the --harness flag is silently ignored and the embedded agent harness is used instead, routing to whichever LM Studio provider is configured as default.\n\nObserved: started execute-loop --local --harness claude --model claude-sonnet-4-6. Every session in the output showed 'model: vidar' or 'model: bragi' and all LLM responses were from qwen3.5-27b. No claude traffic was generated. The claude binary is healthy (ddx agent doctor reports OK). When execute-loop is started with --harness claude and NO --model flag, the claude binary is correctly invoked (confirmed by claude --print process appearing in ps output).\n\nRoot cause hypothesis: the --model flag value is being interpreted as a provider/route key by the embedded agent harness dispatch layer. When the model string matches a known provider name or a catalog entry that maps to the embedded-openai surface, the harness selection silently switches to 'agent' regardless of what --harness specifies. The --harness flag loses the race.\n\nRequired fix: --harness must take strict precedence over any routing implied by --model. If --harness claude is specified and the model string is not a valid claude model ID, the loop should either (a) pass the model string through to the claude binary as-is and let it fail with a clear error, or (b) emit a startup warning 'model X is not a recognized claude model; ignoring --model flag' and proceed with the harness default. Silent rerouting to a different harness is never acceptable.\n\nAdditionally: when the harness override causes a routing mismatch, the error or warning must appear before any bead is claimed, not after execution has started.","events_attachment":"ddx-2ef94940/events.jsonl","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-04-14T08:13:16.992411409Z","id":"ddx-2ef94940","issue_type":"bug","labels":["bug","execute-loop","cli","ux"],"owner":"ddx","priority":1,"session_id":"eb-5e97635e","status":"closed","title":"execute-loop: --harness flag silently ignored when --model is a provider name","updated_at":"2026-04-14T08:13:37.379499959Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:232:{"acceptance":"1. With --provider vidar-omlx + config profile with cheap:qwen/qwen3.6, routing resolves to Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-4bit via discovery override even though catalog's embedded-openai surface has a different concrete ID.\n\n2. When the catalog-resolved ID IS served by the pinned provider, no override fires — catalog wins.\n\n3. Bare-leaf refs (--model-ref qwen3.6, no vendor prefix) also trigger discovery consultation when Provider is pinned.\n\n4. When --provider is NOT set, catalog-only behavior is unchanged (no regression in unpinned mode).\n\n5. Routing event records 'discovery_override' with kind + requested_ref + catalog_resolved + discovery_matched + provider.\n\n6. Regression test covers Profile+Provider+Catalog+Discovery interaction AND bare-leaf variant.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"5328120be55ab6af07a5cd35c7dc7f7a22f30f96","created_at":"2026-04-18T01:05:51.36264259Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ddx-2f5a2284","depends_on_id":"ddx-8610020e","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-18T01:07:26Z"},{"issue_id":"ddx-2f5a2284","depends_on_id":"ddx-0486e601","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-18T01:07:26Z"},{"issue_id":"ddx-2f5a2284","depends_on_id":"ddx-b388f45a","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-18T01:07:26Z"}],"description":"## Superseded scope — narrowed per fresh-eyes review 2026-04-18\n\nThe original bead framing ('fuzzy matcher collapses provider identity; must match against per-provider pool') is now wholly absorbed into ddx-0486e601 (routing: fuzzy matcher normalization + per-provider pool). Both reviewers (codex + opus) flagged the overlap.\n\nWhat remains is the ROUTING-LAYER integration work that sits on top of the discovery-layer fix in ddx-0486e601: making the catalog/Profile paths actually CONSULT discovery when req.Provider is pinned. Today, fuzzy match fires only on the uncataloged ModelPin branch (routing.go:193-225). The ModelRef path (routing.go:233-247) and the Profile path (routing.go:248-262) are catalog-only; even after ddx-0486e601 lands, a Profile tier's model_override will still resolve straight from the catalog without checking whether the catalog-resolved concrete ID is actually served by the pinned provider.\n\n## Narrowed scope\n\n1. In routing.go's ModelRef branch: after catalog resolution, if req.Provider is set and discovery is available, check whether the catalog-resolved concrete ID appears on the pinned provider's discovered model list. If yes, proceed. If no, run fuzzy match (via ddx-0486e601's per-provider matcher) against the pinned provider using the ORIGINAL ref (pre-catalog) as input. On fuzzy hit, override the catalog result with the provider-native ID and emit a 'discovery_override' routing event.\n\n2. Same integration in the Profile branch (routing.go:248-262) so tier overrides participate in the override.\n\n3. **Bare-leaf refs** (per opus review): when --model-ref is a bare leaf with no vendor prefix (e.g. 'qwen3.6' vs 'qwen/qwen3.6') AND catalog lookup MISSES (falling into the ModelPin branch), the discovery-consultation hook must still fire when req.Provider is set. Prevents UX asymmetry where 'qwen/qwen3.6' works but 'qwen3.6' doesn't.\n\n4. When req.Provider is NOT set, preserve catalog-only behavior (SD-015 intent for unpinned mode).\n\n5. Emit structured routing events on every override: {kind:'discovery_override', requested_ref, catalog_resolved, discovery_matched, provider, reason}.\n\n## Files likely touched\n\n- cli/internal/agent/routing.go — ModelRef branch + Profile branch\n- cli/internal/agent/routing_test.go — regression covering Profile+Provider+Catalog+Discovery interaction and bare-leaf refs\n\n## Depends on\n\n- ddx-8610020e (RouteRequest.Provider field) — routing needs to see req.Provider\n- ddx-0486e601 (fuzzy normalization + per-provider matcher) — this bead calls it","id":"ddx-2f5a2284","issue_type":"bug","labels":["ddx","phase:build","kind:bug","area:agent","area:routing","area:discovery"],"notes":"Superseded by agent-1a486c2e — single routing engine in agent/internal/routing","parent":"ddx-2d974641","priority":2,"spec-id":"SD-015","status":"closed","title":"routing: ModelRef/Profile paths must consult discovery for --provider + catalog override","updated_at":"2026-04-18T22:43:47.001714558Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:234:{"acceptance":"1. `bash -lc '! rg -n -e \"\\\\bddx agent (run|execute-bead|execute-loop)\\\\b|--harnesses\\\\b|--quorum\\\\b|--profile\\\\b|DDx-side ResolveRoute|PreResolved|profile_ladders|model_overrides\" docs/helix/02-design/solution-designs/SD-011-agent-skills.md docs/helix/02-design/solution-designs/SD-012-git-awareness.md docs/helix/02-design/solution-designs/SD-013-multi-agent-coordination.md docs/helix/02-design/solution-designs/SD-022-gql-svelte-migration.md'` passes.\\n2. Diff is limited to docs wording/classification in the in-scope files.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-04-30T04:06:10Z","claimed-machine":"sindri","claimed-pid":"3740593","closing_commit_sha":"138389edb5c41f9270152871edd96b7cf11825f0","created_at":"2026-04-30T04:04:18.63542609Z","description":"Sub-bead of ddx-b4c27896. Scrub active solution designs that reference removed agent command surfaces.\n\nIn-scope files:\n- docs/helix/02-design/solution-designs/SD-011-agent-skills.md\n- docs/helix/02-design/solution-designs/SD-012-git-awareness.md\n- docs/helix/02-design/solution-designs/SD-013-multi-agent-coordination.md\n- docs/helix/02-design/solution-designs/SD-022-gql-svelte-migration.md\n\nRequired changes:\n- Use run/try/work terminology for active execution workflows.\n- Replace legacy execute-loop/execute-bead command examples.\n- Use skill composition language instead of core quorum/harness dispatch flags.\n\nOut of scope:\n- Other solution designs and technical designs handled by sibling beads.\n- Code changes.","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-04-30T04:06:10.424637153Z","id":"ddx-3074f00b","issue_type":"task","labels":["helix","phase:build","area:docs","area:design","kind:cleanup"],"owner":"erik","parent":"ddx-b4c27896","priority":1,"spec_id":"FEAT-006,FEAT-010","status":"closed","title":"docs-design: scrub solution designs part 1 for execution boundary","updated_at":"2026-04-30T04:07:13.312643176Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:247:{"acceptance":"BuildLandingGateContext + EvaluateRequiredGatesForResult exist in cli/internal/agent/, exported, with unit tests covering: govern-IDs-empty noop path, govern-IDs-present worktree+pin lifecycle, cleanup-on-error path, gate-pass writes checks.json with PASS, gate-fail writes checks.json with FAIL. Existing LandBeadResult delegates to EvaluateRequiredGatesForResult instead of inlining the same logic. Build clean, tests green.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"3754e5fbd0b147c2897892d34daf11daad673054","created_at":"2026-04-19T16:25:01.850399319Z","description":"Both the interactive execute-bead path (ddx-14c0e790) and server execute-loop path (ddx-e437ebc1) need the same setup before invoking gate eval: pin ResultRev, create an ephemeral worktree at that ref, extract governing IDs from manifest, and arrange cleanup. Extract once to prevent drift.\n\nSignature:\n  func BuildLandingGateContext(projectRoot string, res *ExecuteBeadResult, gitOps GitOps) (wtPath string, governIDs []string, cleanup func(), err error)\n\nBehavior:\n- Read filepath.Join(projectRoot, res.ManifestFile); call ExtractGoverningIDsFromManifest.\n- If govern IDs empty: return (\"\", nil, noop, nil) — no checkout needed.\n- Otherwise: pin ResultRev via refs/ddx/gate-pins/\u003cbeadID\u003e/\u003cattemptID\u003e, then WorktreeAdd a temp worktree at that ref. Cleanup unpins and removes the worktree.\n\nAlso extract EvaluateRequiredGatesForResult(wtPath, governIDs, res, projectRoot) — a thin wrapper around evaluateRequiredGates that also writes checks.json and populates res.GateResults / RequiredExecSummary / RatchetEvidence. Currently inline at LandBeadResult lines 220-245; lift so both paths share it.\n\nThis bead lands in isolation with unit tests against fakeExecuteBeadGit. Sub-tasks (interactive + server + backward-compat) all use it.","id":"ddx-341425a4","issue_type":"task","labels":["ddx","area:agent","area:exec","kind:refactor"]