.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:274:{"acceptance":"(1) cli/internal/agent/providerstatus (or similar) package exists with a Probe function returning a unified status struct. (2) providers/models/check/route-status all render from the same underlying struct. (3) Timeout is consistent (or documented per caller). (4) Existing command output is backwards-compatible (same fields surfaced to users).","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-04-15T07:39:32Z","claimed-machine":"eitri","claimed-pid":"3766264","closing_commit_sha":"62e96010a676ef1958e2bfdecf24eab1906fcea0","created_at":"2026-04-15T05:00:42.171059528Z","description":"Opus epic review (2026-04-15) flagged 4 disconnected provider-status schemas across the visibility commands:\n- providerStatusEntry in cli/cmd/agent_providers.go:17\n- checkResult in cli/cmd/agent_check.go:17\n- routeCandidateStatus in cli/cmd/agent_route_status.go:69\n- inline probing in cli/cmd/agent_models.go:95\n\nEach reimplements oai.DiscoverModels + status classification with different timeouts (3s/3s/5s/5s) and different result shapes. A scripting user has to learn four schemas to read the same underlying data.\n\nIntroduce a single providerstatus.Probe(ctx, cfg, name) returning one struct that all four commands render.","events_attachment":"ddx-3b804e2e/events.jsonl","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-04-15T07:48:32.8468703Z","id":"ddx-3b804e2e","issue_type":"chore","labels":["ddx","phase:build","kind:refactor","area:agent","area:cli","source:opus-review"],"owner":"ddx","parent":"ddx-bd0691fe","priority":2,"session_id":"eb-b264738a","status":"closed","title":"refactor(agent): unify providerStatus/checkResult/routeCandidateStatus into shared Probe primitive","updated_at":"2026-04-15T07:49:00.543902293Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:275:{"acceptance":"SD-023 (or equivalent) written covering: comparison arm isolation; grading rubric and scoring pipeline; replay source-of-truth (session logs vs evidence bundles); relationship to 'ddx agent compare/benchmark/quorum' commands already implemented. Linked from FEAT-019.md and TP-019.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"8608519a7b481a2180664d0f2f536b237a950e61","created_at":"2026-04-21T02:56:46.622680416Z","description":"FEAT-019 is P1 and complex (dispatch same prompt to multiple harnesses, capture structured outputs, grading, replay), but has no Solution Design. TP-019 cannot be authored until the architecture is defined. Decide: use SD-019 slot (currently multi-project-server-topology — rename that SD to SD-019-multi-project-server-topology is fine but causes confusion) OR allocate a new SD number. Recommended: SD-023-agent-evaluation.md because SD-019 is already taken by multi-project topology.","events_attachment":"ddx-3b91ca7a/events.jsonl","id":"ddx-3b91ca7a","issue_type":"task","labels":["helix","phase:design","area:agent","kind:design"],"parent":"ddx-cbd20059","priority":2,"spec-id":"FEAT-019","status":"closed","title":"design: create SD-019-agent-evaluation.md (comparison, grading, replay architecture)","updated_at":"2026-04-21T12:32:59.028563521Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:276:{"acceptance":"1. cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./... passes\n2. grep -rnE 'profile_ladders|model_overrides|ProfileLadders|ModelOverrides|ResolveProfileLadder|ResolveTierModelRef|AdaptiveMinTier|--escalate|--override-model' cli/ docs/ --include='*.go' --include='*.md' --include='*.yaml' --include='*.json' returns no matches in DDx source files (vendored node_modules and this bead's own description excluded)\n3. cd /home/erik/Projects/ddx \u0026\u0026 /home/erik/.local/bin/ddx work --once --local runs cleanly with no deprecation warnings and no flags needed\n4. A fixture project carrying agent.routing.profile_ladders OR agent.routing.model_overrides in its .ddx/config.yaml causes any ddx command that loads config to exit non-zero with a message naming the offending field\n5. /home/erik/.local/bin/ddx work --help; /home/erik/.local/bin/ddx agent run --help; /home/erik/.local/bin/ddx agent execute-bead --help — none of these show --escalate or --override-model\n6. docs/adaptive-min-tier.md and docs/migrations/routing-config.md are either deleted or replaced with single-line removal stubs","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-04-29T22:03:35Z","claimed-machine":"eitri","claimed-pid":"932496","closing_commit_sha":"6125fa05cd2adf6a99a0a9338024ebe4fbc3be4d","created_at":"2026-04-29T19:06:40.635889422Z","description":"## Goal\n\nDelete `agent.routing.profile_ladders`, `agent.routing.model_overrides`, the `--escalate` and `--override-model` flags, all their consumers, and the deprecation warnings. The duplicated routing layer is dead — the corpse should not haunt every config load.\n\nThe migration `ddx-87fb72c2` made these opt-in. This bead completes the migration: opt-in becomes opt-out becomes gone.\n\n## Scope (delete with prejudice)\n\n### Config schema\n- `cli/internal/config/types.go` — delete `RoutingConfig.ProfileLadders` and `RoutingConfig.ModelOverrides` fields (and `defaultProfileLadders`, `DefaultProfileLadders()`).\n- `cli/internal/config/schema/config.schema.json` — delete the `profile_ladders` and `model_overrides` properties.\n- `cli/internal/config/config.go` — delete the deprecation warning code paths that detect these fields and print the migration hint. Hard reject any project config that still sets them: clear error pointing at the (then-archived) migration doc, exit non-zero. Same blast radius as `default_harness` already gets.\n- `cli/internal/config/routing_migration_test.go` — delete or repurpose to test the new hard-reject behavior.\n\n### CLI flags\n- `cli/cmd/agent_cmd.go` — delete `--escalate` and `--override-model` flag definitions and their plumbing into `WorkerSpec` / RouteRequest. The `WorkerSpec.Escalate` field added by `ddx-c7081f89` becomes dead and goes too.\n- `cli/cmd/agent_execute_loop_*.go` — same.\n- Any flag wiring in the worker submit path (`cli/internal/server/server.go`, `cli/internal/server/workers.go`).\n\n### Helpers and consumers\n- `cli/internal/agent/profile_ladder.go` — delete entirely (`ResolveProfileLadder`, `ResolveTierModelRef`, `NormalizeRoutingProfile`'s ladder semantics, the test seam call counters, `DefaultRoutingProfile`).\n- `cli/internal/escalation/escalation.go` — delete `AdaptiveMinTier`, `AdaptiveMinTierResult`, `AdaptiveMinTierThreshold`, `AdaptiveMinTierMinSamples`, `TierResolver`, `classifyAttemptTier`, `TierOrder`, `TiersInRange`, `tierIndex`. Keep `EscalationSummary`, `TierAttemptRecord`, `BuildEscalationSummary`, `AppendEscalationSummaryEvent`, `EscalationWinningExhausted`, `EscalatableStatuses`, `ShouldEscalate`, `IsInfrastructureFailure`, `ProviderCooldownDuration`, `FormatTierAttemptBody`, `BeadEventAppender`, `SuccessStatus` — these are still used by other paths (loop status, bead events, cooldown).\n- `cli/internal/server/workers.go:658-820` — delete the entire escalation-on branch (the `if !escalationEnabled { ... } else { ...tier loop... }` split). `escalationEnabled` always false; collapse to the single-call path.\n- `cli/cmd/agent_route_status.go` — drop the `--adaptive` flag and `reset` subcommand if they target the now-deleted state. Keep the rest of route-status.\n- `docs/adaptive-min-tier.md` — delete.\n\n### Documentation\n- `docs/migrations/routing-config.md` — delete (or replace with a one-line stub: \"agent.routing.profile_ladders and agent.routing.model_overrides were removed in vX.Y.Z; configs that still set them are rejected at load.\").\n- `cli/internal/server/frontend/README.md`, `CHANGELOG.md` — search and remove any user-facing references to `--escalate` or `--override-model`.\n\n### Tests\n- Delete tests that exclusively cover the deleted paths: `*_escalation_*_test.go`, `profile_ladder_test.go`, `routing_migration_test.go`, etc. Where a test covers BOTH a deleted path and a kept path, narrow it to the kept path.\n- Add one test that asserts `ddx work --once --local` on a project that still has `routing.profile_ladders` in its config exits non-zero with an error message naming the field.\n\n## Affirmative non-goals\n\n- Do **not** preserve any \"transition\" behavior. There is no warning-then-error grace period; `ddx-87fb72c2` already shipped the warning. This bead is the deletion.\n- Do **not** keep dead `Escalate` / `MinTier` / `MaxTier` / `ModelRef` fields on `WorkerSpec` \"for future use\". If something needs them later, file a fresh bead.\n- Do **not** keep the helpers in case some out-of-tree consumer imports them. DDx is a binary, not a library.\n- Do **not** touch agent SDK internals — `ProfileEscalationLadder` and `escalateProfileLadder` live agent-side and stay.\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- Default profile change (separate bead if pursued).\n- HistoricalSuccess injection into `RouteRequest.Inputs` (separate bead).\n- Bead-id resolver bug (`ddx-7eab13a6`) — already filed.\n- The 12 malformed-ID beads — `ddx-7eab13a6` covers their repair.\n\n## Acceptance\n\n1. `cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./...` passes (full tree, not just routing packages — the kept escalation helpers may have other callers).\n2. `grep -rnE 'profile_ladders|model_overrides|ProfileLadders|ModelOverrides|ResolveProfileLadder|ResolveTierModelRef|AdaptiveMinTier|--escalate|--override-model' cli/ docs/ --include='*.go' --include='*.md' --include='*.yaml' --include='*.json'` returns matches only in:\n   - this bead's own description (if grepped from .ddx/beads.jsonl)\n   - the deletion test fixture / commit message\n   - upstream-vendored code under cli/internal/server/frontend/node_modules/ if any\n   No matches in source files.\n3. `cd /home/erik/Projects/ddx \u0026\u0026 /home/erik/.local/bin/ddx work --once --local` against the current project (with `agent.routing` already removed) runs cleanly, no warnings, no flags needed.\n4. A test fixture project with `agent.routing.profile_ladders: ...` in its `.ddx/config.yaml` causes any `ddx ...` command that loads config to exit non-zero with a message identifying the field. Same for `agent.routing.model_overrides`.\n5. `--escalate` and `--override-model` flags are gone from `--help` output of `ddx work`, `ddx agent run`, `ddx agent execute-bead`, `ddx agent execute-loop`. Verifiable: `/home/erik/.local/bin/ddx work --help 2\u003e\u00261 | grep -E 'escalate|override-model'` returns nothing.\n6. `docs/adaptive-min-tier.md` and `docs/migrations/routing-config.md` are either deleted or replaced with single-line stubs noting the removal.\n\n## Rollback\n\nIf the deletion proves too aggressive, revert the deletion commits. The migration doc (`docs/migrations/routing-config.md`) at HEAD before deletion has the full feature description; the git history retains the helpers.","events_attachment":"ddx-3bd7396a/events.jsonl","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-04-29T22:55:05.634439786Z","id":"ddx-3bd7396a","issue_type":"chore","labels":["area:routing","area:agent","area:config","kind:cleanup","kind:deletion"],"owner":"erik","priority":1,"session_id":"eb-b4716fb6","status":"closed","title":"delete deprecated routing config + flags + warnings with prejudice (profile_ladders, model_overrides, --escalate, --override-model, AdaptiveMinTier)","updated_at":"2026-04-29T22:55:49.899491937Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:277:{"acceptance":"- [ ] WorkerManager.AgentRunnerFactory field deleted\n- [ ] Tests pass (workers_test.go and providers_test.go no longer reference AgentRunnerFactory per ddx-dac03f0a)","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"cd6b07cb67c3abeb778c82d2ea592be7efa82c24","created_at":"2026-04-19T02:38:40.97926124Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ddx-3bf91ebf","depends_on_id":"ddx-378d381f","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-19T02:39:19Z"}],"description":"server/workers.go uses the same tier-escalation primitives (TiersInRange, TierAttemptRecord, FormatTierAttemptBody, AppendEscalationSummaryEvent, ShouldEscalate, ModelTier). Same migration pattern as cmd/agent_cmd.go.\n\nPlus: drop the deprecated AgentRunnerFactory field (already noted as dead by ddx-bc1e99ec). Tests in workers_test.go and providers_test.go (already migrated by ddx-dac03f0a) no longer set it.\n\nPre-condition: tier-escalation decision bead.","id":"ddx-3bf91ebf","issue_type":"task","labels":["phase:build","area:server","kind:migration"],"notes":"Per ddx-378d381f decision: tier-escalation symbols stay in DDx. The tier-escalation refs in server/workers.go continue to work. The ONLY remaining work in this bead is dropping the deprecated AgentRunnerFactory field from WorkerManager (already a no-op since ddx-bc1e99ec marked it dead). Re-scope: small cleanup only.","parent":"ddx-62b04ccd","priority":1,"status":"closed","title":"Migrate server/workers.go tier-escalation callers + remove deprecated AgentRunnerFactory field","updated_at":"2026-04-19T03:14:03.433535062Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:278:{"acceptance":"1. Loop has triage step after each attempt's terminal event. 2. Per-failure-mode triage policy in .ddx/config.yaml. 3. Triage outcomes (re-attempt-with-context, escalate-tier, needs_human) align exactly with TD-031 TriageContract (per ddx-673833f4). **No new persisted statuses introduced — all triage state lives in labels (e.g., triage:needs-human) and events per bd/br compatibility (ADR-004).** 4. Default: BLOCK→re-attempt-with-context, then escalate-tier, then add 'triage:needs-human' label. 5. Lock-error handling delegates to ddx-da11a34a's implementation; this bead does NOT duplicate retry/backoff logic. Triage policy entry for lock errors invokes the lock-bead's published API. 6. Tests: BLOCK→re-attempt, BLOCK→escalate, lock-error→delegates-to-lock-bead, no_changes→re-evaluate. 7. Out of scope: rate-limit handling, quota-pause handling, lock-retry implementation, status-enum modification. 8. needs_human stays a LABEL per current code (cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_review_triage.go:19-23) and TD's resolution. 9. **schema_compat_test.go round-trip passes after this bead lands.**","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"4221a8f3596a23aedd4bab355865d023c9b3f344","created_at":"2026-05-02T13:04:11.868818227Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ddx-3c154349","depends_on_id":"ddx-673833f4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-05-02T18:14:01Z"},{"issue_id":"ddx-3c154349","depends_on_id":"ddx-7d7a17c8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-05-02T19:04:17Z"}],"description":"Currently when a bead hits a post-merge review BLOCK, the drain loop emits the BLOCK event, leaves the bead open, and moves to the next ready bead. The BLOCK then sits in the queue waiting for a human. Same for many substantive execution_failed cases — no automated triage.\n\nThis bead handles BLOCK + substantive failures only. Two SEPARATE beads cover related-but-distinct concerns:\n- ddx-aede917d: drain pause/resume on quota exhaustion (Fizeau-side state, DDx consumes typed error)\n- ddx-c6e3db02: per-bead rate-limit retry honoring Retry-After (provider stays in rotation)\n\nFailure modes triaged HERE:\n- post-merge review BLOCK → either (a) re-attempt-with-context (BLOCK reasons embedded in next prompt), (b) escalate to next tier in the S10_2 ladder, or (c) file follow-up bead capturing BLOCK reasons + mark original needs_human\n- 'staging tracker: Unable to create .git/index.lock' (git contention — see  / ddx-da11a34a) → retry with backoff after lock clears\n- substantive execution_failed (probe_ok+exec_fail; agent finished but produced no useful diff or wrong shape) → escalate per S10 ladder\n- 'no_changes' (agent decided nothing to do) → re-evaluate against the bead AC; if still seems valid, file a clarification follow-up rather than mark already_satisfied\n\nTriage policy is config-driven, per-failure-mode mapping in .ddx/config.yaml triage:. Default: BLOCK→re-attempt-with-context, then escalate-tier on second BLOCK, then needs_human on third.\n\nNOT in scope: rate-limit handling (ddx-c6e3db02) and quota-pause handling (ddx-aede917d) — those are separate beads with their own infrastructure.","events_attachment":"ddx-3c154349/events.jsonl","execute-loop-no-changes-count":2,"id":"ddx-3c154349","issue_type":"task","labels":["phase:2","story:10","area:agent","kind:fix","observed-failure"],"notes":"decomposed into 3 children: framework (.execute-bead-wt-ddx-3c154349-20260502T131050-bf2d17f5-0a700bd2), review-block integration (.execute-bead-wt-ddx-3c154349-20260502T131050-bf2d17f5-5f67936e), lock/execution_failed/no_changes integration (.execute-bead-wt-ddx-3c154349-20260502T131050-bf2d17f5-2b64cb0a). Children 2 and 3 depend on child 1.\n\nREVIEW:BLOCK\n\nDiff contains only execution manifest/result metadata for the parent bead. No source changes implementing triage step, config policy, BLOCK re-attempt, lock retry, or tests. Parent was decomposed into 3 children; implementation lives there, not here.","parent":"ddx-e34994e2","priority":1,"session_id":"eb-7ec1c8ee","status":"closed","title":"ddx work: auto-triage on review BLOCK + substantive execution failures","updated_at":"2026-05-03T21:54:33.582788548Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:279:{"acceptance":"execute-bead prompt contract explicitly invites no_changes with a rationale. The fake-agent test harness seeds a no_changes rationale file; execute_bead_test.go asserts ExecuteBeadResult.NoChangesRationale is populated; execute-loop uses the rationale to classify 'already_satisfied' when it references a prior commit SHA or test name; the rendered log (ddx server workers log) shows the rationale on its own line; 'agent made no commits' no longer appears without context.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-04-14T08:21:48Z","claimed-machine":"eitri","claimed-pid":"1412283","closing_commit_sha":"f495bf65ad5e6906f85e7c5260ce12f8c76a20be","created_at":"2026-04-14T04:03:21.715664968Z","description":"Today when execute-bead exits with no_changes, the operator sees 'agent made no commits' and nothing else. That's useless for triage — the operator cannot tell whether:\\n- the bead is genuinely already satisfied (work present in a prior commit)\\n- the agent gave up because it couldn't find the relevant files\\n- the agent classified the task as ambiguous or too risky\\n- the agent hit a tool limit or context cap\\n- the prompt contract was unclear\\n\\nThe fix is to make no_changes a structured result that carries a short rationale from the agent itself, written at the point where the agent decided not to commit. Example of what the operator should see:\\n\\n  status:    no_changes\\n  rationale: The epic filter requested by this bead was already added in\\n             commit 1da6495 (cli/internal/bead/store.go readyFiltered). I\\n             reviewed the current code and tests, confirmed the filter\\n             excludes 'epic' beads from ReadyExecution, and verified\\n             TestReadyExecutionExcludesEpics exists and passes. Nothing\\n             to do. Ref: 1da6495, TestReadyExecutionExcludesEpics.\\n\\nThis is specifically the case that motivated this bead: a continuous-drain worker processed ddx-b44ca394 ('Prevent execute-loop from launching open epics by default') after the epic filter had already been implemented on main. The agent instead made a synthesized no-op commit that only retargeted 17 .claude/skills/helix-* symlinks, which the loop classified as 'success' because a commit was produced. Had no_changes carried a rationale pointing at the prior commit, the loop could have closed the bead as 'already_satisfied' and moved on cleanly.\\n\\nScope:\\n1. Execute-bead prompt contract must explicitly instruct the agent: if you determine the bead's work is already present or cannot be done, report that in a structured way — do NOT make a synthesized commit to 'land something'. Today the prompt says 'Making no commits (no_changes) should be rare' which actively pushes agents toward the wrong behavior.\\n2. The agent's exit mechanism needs a way to carry a rationale string back. Simplest version: the agent writes a file to the worktree like .ddx/executions/\u003cattempt-id\u003e/no_changes_rationale.txt before exiting. ExecuteBead reads it if no commits were produced and attaches the text to the result.NoChangesRationale field.\\n3. The ExecuteBeadResult struct gains a NoChangesRationale string field, populated only when outcome == no_changes. Status: success and the unused 'reason' field need not change.\\n4. execute-loop close semantics: when no_changes arrives with a non-empty rationale pointing at a prior commit, the loop can optionally close the bead as already_satisfied with the rationale recorded in the close event body (instead of waiting for MaxNoChangesBeforeClose=3 strikes). Gate this behind a 'rationale references existing commit' heuristic to avoid flapping — if the rationale is a vague 'nothing to do', keep current cooldown behavior.\\n5. ddx server worker log should render the rationale prominently, not bury it in session metadata.\\n6. The prompt contract note that no_changes should be 'rare' is replaced with: 'If the work is already present, say so and provide a reference (commit SHA, test name, file path). A well-justified no_changes is always preferred to a cosmetic synthesized commit.'","events_attachment":"ddx-3c30bfa2/events.jsonl","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-04-14T08:43:48.707134432Z","id":"ddx-3c30bfa2","issue_type":"task","owner":"ddx","priority":1,"session_id":"eb-reconcile-f495bf6","status":"closed","title":"no_changes reports must include a rationale the operator can act on","updated_at":"2026-04-14T14:12:46.040411073Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:280:{"acceptance":"1. cli/go.mod is bumped to a Fizeau release whose ServiceConfig interface has no ModelRoute* methods. 2. cli/internal/agent/serviceconfig.go contains no ModelRouteNames, ModelRouteCandidates, ModelRouteConfig, ServiceModelRouteConfig, model_routes, or route key references. 3. ddx agent route-status still reports live providers/models with status, cost, usage/quota, and power. 4. rg -n 'model_routes|ModelRoute|model route|route key|No model routes|Requested model route' cli/cmd cli/internal/agent cli/internal/server website/content/docs/cli/commands/ddx_agent_route-status.md returns no hits. 5. cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./cmd -run TestAgentRouteStatus -count=1 \u0026\u0026 go test ./internal/agent -run 'TestFormatSessionLogLines|TestTailSessionLogs' -count=1 passes.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"288e5db15e7341290ac0c28e55dfb565e62a2ba2","created_at":"2026-05-05T01:53:04.176111186Z","description":"DDx no longer exposes or depends on model_routes. After the upstream Fizeau ServiceConfig contract removes ModelRouteNames, ModelRouteCandidates, and ModelRouteConfig, delete the no-op compatibility methods from cli/internal/agent/serviceconfig.go. These methods currently exist only because github.com/DocumentDrivenDX/fizeau v0.10.7 requires them; they must not be treated as a DDx routing concept. Also keep ddx agent route-status on live provider/model inventory: providers, models, quota, usage, cost, power, and current ResolveRoute preview. In-scope files: cli/go.mod, cli/go.sum, cli/internal/agent/serviceconfig.go, route-status tests if the Fizeau API shape changes. Out-of-scope: reintroducing any model_routes config, route table, route key, or candidate-list surface in DDx.","events_attachment":"ddx-3c4618e3/events.jsonl","execute-loop-last-detail":"no_changes","execute-loop-last-status":"no_changes","execute-loop-no-changes-count":3,"execute-loop-retry-after":"2026-05-05T20:14:14Z","id":"ddx-3c4618e3","issue_type":"task","labels":["area:agent","area:routing","kind:cleanup","triage:needs-investigation"],"priority":0,"status":"closed","title":"Drop Fizeau model route compatibility stubs from DDx","updated_at":"2026-05-05T16:15:28.739105523Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:282:{"acceptance":"1. On a host with a pinned provider P whose catalog lookup only resolves cheap-tier model_override, running 'ddx work --once --local --provider P' caps at cheap tier and logs a routing event indicating which tiers were filtered out and why. No dispatch to a model that returns 404.\n\n2. Regression test in cli/internal/agent/routing_test.go: construct a RouteRequest with ProviderAffinity set to a provider whose catalog surface only has a cheap-tier mapping; assert the produced ladder contains only the cheap candidate and carries a capped_reason string naming the missing smart-tier model + the pinned provider.\n\n3. When --provider is NOT pinned, existing escalation behavior is unchanged (regression test).\n\n4. --max-tier cap continues to work as an explicit override and is honored even when the provider-affinity filter would allow a higher tier.\n\n5. With ddx-e59e7fe8 and this bead landed, 'ddx work --once --local --provider vidar-omlx' (no --model, no --max-tier) either completes cleanly at cheap tier or emits a clear 'no tier resolves' diagnostic — no opaque 404 escalation.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"5328120be55ab6af07a5cd35c7dc7f7a22f30f96","created_at":"2026-04-18T00:58:05.964534969Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ddx-3c5ba7cc","depends_on_id":"ddx-e59e7fe8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-18T00:58:11Z"},{"issue_id":"ddx-3c5ba7cc","depends_on_id":"ddx-8610020e","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-18T01:07:26Z"},{"issue_id":"ddx-3c5ba7cc","depends_on_id":"ddx-0486e601","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-18T01:14:30Z"}],"description":"## Problem\n\nWhen 'ddx work --provider P' is invoked with a pinned provider and the cheap-tier attempt fails (for any reason: execution_failed, land_conflict, no_changes repeated, etc.), DDx escalates to the standard or smart tier using the project config's tier model overrides WITHOUT checking whether those escalation-target models actually exist on the pinned provider.\n\nObserved on eitri 2026-04-17 (DDx v0.6.0-alpha22):\n\n    .ddx/config.yaml:\n      agent:\n        routing:\n          profile_priority: [cheap]\n          model_overrides:\n            cheap:  qwen/qwen3.6\n            fast:   kimi/k2.5\n            smart:  minimax/minimax-m2.7\n\n    $ ddx work --once --local --provider vidar-omlx\n    # cheap-tier attempt on vidar-omlx fails (for whatever reason — in this\n    # session it was catalog-missing model on vidar-omlx; see ddx-e59e7fe8)\n    # smart-tier escalation tries minimax/minimax-m2.7 — also routes to\n    # vidar-omlx because of --provider pinning — fails with 404 'Model not\n    # found' because vidar-omlx has MiniMax-M2.5-MLX-4bit, not m2.7.\n    #\n    # Final outcome: 'escalation exhausted: ...404 Not Found...'\n\nEvidence: .ddx/executions/20260418T005017-ac81ac97/.\n\n## What escalation should do instead\n\nWhen --provider P is pinned, tier escalation options (in preference order):\n\n1. **Restrict escalation to models that resolve on the pinned provider.**\n   For each tier in profile_priority after the failing tier, check whether the\n   tier's model_override resolves (via catalog) to a concrete ID that the\n   pinned provider serves. If yes, use it. If no, skip that tier.\n\n2. **If no higher tier resolves on the pinned provider, cap escalation.**\n   Surface a clear diagnostic: 'escalation capped at cheap tier — smart\n   (minimax/minimax-m2.7) does not resolve on provider vidar-omlx'. Honor\n   --max-tier as a hard cap regardless of provider pinning.\n\n3. **Do NOT silently widen to a different provider unless the user opts in.**\n   'ddx work --provider P' is a pinning directive; spontaneously routing to\n   openrouter because smart-tier doesn't fit on P violates the user's intent\n   and leaks cost/quota to the wrong place.\n\n4. **Separate case: --provider is NOT pinned (no flag).** Current behavior\n   of picking a different provider for higher tiers is fine; this bead is\n   only about the pinned case.\n\n## Fix sketch\n\nIn cli/internal/agent/routing.go (or wherever tier escalation lives):\n\n1. When the runner sees req.ProviderAffinity != '' (or equivalent pinned-\n   provider signal), build the tier ladder by filtering to tiers whose\n   model_override resolves on that provider via the catalog.\n\n2. If the filtered ladder is empty (not even cheap resolves), fail fast with\n   a route-plan error before claiming the bead, not after a 14s dispatch.\n\n3. Emit a routing event on the bead recording the effective ladder, e.g.:\n   {resolved_provider: 'vidar-omlx', effective_tiers: ['cheap'], capped_reason:\n   'smart-tier minimax/minimax-m2.7 not served by vidar-omlx'}.\n\n## Files likely touched\n\n- cli/internal/agent/routing.go — tier escalation logic, provider-affinity filter\n- cli/internal/agent/routing_test.go — regression: pinned provider + smart-tier override that doesn't resolve on that provider should cap at cheap, not 404 at dispatch\n- cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_orchestrator.go — the escalation loop; needs to read the effective ladder\n\n## Depends on\n\n- ddx-e59e7fe8 (catalog: omlx surface) — escalation-filter logic needs catalog-lookup to know what resolves where. Land that first or in the same change.\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- ddx-6a5dfe35 parse bug — a separate dispatch-layer defect.\n- Changing .ddx/config.yaml's shipped tier defaults — separate editorial call.","id":"ddx-3c5ba7cc","issue_type":"task","labels":["ddx","phase:build","kind:implementation","area:agent","area:routing"],"notes":"Superseded by agent-1a486c2e — single routing engine in agent/internal/routing","parent":"ddx-2d974641","priority":1,"spec-id":"FEAT-006","status":"closed","title":"routing: tier escalation must respect --provider affinity","updated_at":"2026-04-18T22:43:46.899330352Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:285:{"acceptance":"1. A test bead is filed with AC 'write a one-line report named hello.md describing the current Go version'. 2. ddx work --once executes the bead with claude harness. 3. The resulting commit includes a hello.md file under .ddx/executions/\u003crun-id\u003e/, NOT in /tmp. 4. If verification fails, the fix is reopened as a follow-up bead with a stricter prompt.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-05-02T03:41:39Z","claimed-machine":"eitri","claimed-pid":"1329405","closing_commit_sha":"178449742852a45b04e4e5c5979319d44ec7e173","created_at":"2026-05-02T03:40:11.399080574Z","description":"Commit 6473f3fa updated cli/internal/agent/execute_bead.go to instruct agents to write investigation reports under .ddx/executions/\u003crun-id\u003e/ instead of /tmp. The fix landed too late to help B15a/B21 in the redesign drain. Now that v0.6.2-alpha4 is installed with the fix, verify the system prompt actually steers agents correctly. Strategy: file a tiny test bead with an 'output a report' AC, observe whether the agent writes to .ddx/executions/ or /tmp.","events_attachment":"ddx-3d2ed549/events.jsonl","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-05-02T03:44:39.404028099Z","id":"ddx-3d2ed549","issue_type":"task","labels":["area:agent","kind:test","validation"],"owner":"erik","priority":2,"session_id":"eb-3264b7e8","status":"closed","title":"Verify execute-bead /tmp evidence pattern fix end-to-end","updated_at":"2026-05-02T03:45:17.714111457Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:289:{"acceptance":"DDx docs or Scans the current project's execution-ready bead queue, claims the next\nready bead, runs ddx agent execute-bead from the project root, records the\nstructured result, and continues until no unattempted ready work remains.\n\nUsage:\n  ddx agent execute-loop [flags]\n\nFlags:\n      --effort string            Effort level\n      --from string              Base git revision to start from (default: HEAD)\n      --harness string           Agent harness to use\n  -h, --help                     help for execute-loop\n      --json                     Output loop result as JSON\n      --model string             Model override\n      --once                     Process at most one ready bead\n      --poll-interval duration   Poll interval for continuous scanning; zero drains current ready work and exits\n\nGlobal Flags:\n      --config string              config file (default is $HOME/.ddx.yml)\n      --library-base-path string   override path for DDx library location\n  -v, --verbose                    verbose output explain how execute-loop chooses the next bead when multiple execution-ready beads exist, including any priority/stable-order tie-breakers; if current behavior is not deterministic enough for workflow consumers, the command or docs are updated so the ordering contract is explicit and testable","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","created_at":"2026-04-10T22:41:49.885480428Z","description":"HELIX is now designing against  as the queue-drain contract. Local help says execute-loop scans the project's execution-ready queue and claims the next ready bead, but it does not explain the selection order or tie-breakers when multiple ready beads exist. We need a documented and ideally machine-visible contract for how priority, dependency readiness, and stable ordering interact so higher-level workflows can shape parent/child/dependency topology confidently.","id":"ddx-3e25a7ac","issue_type":"task","labels":["ddx","phase:design","area:agents","area:tracker","area:docs"],"notes":"duplicate of ddx-97540661 created by broken execute-loop run","priority":0,"spec-id":"DDX-agent-execute-loop","status":"closed","title":"Clarify execute-loop ready-queue ordering and selection semantics","updated_at":"2026-04-10T22:44:18.706112991Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:291:{"acceptance":"1. execute_bead_loop pre_merge step runs all applicable checks (filtered by AppliesTo) in parallel before merge-back.\n2. Any status=block or status=error aborts the merge and preserves the worktree per existing iteration-preservation conventions.\n3. checks_bypass annotation on the bead skips the named check and records an event with the reason; missing reason -\u003e bypass rejected.\n4. E2E test: dummy-fail fixture causes merge abort, worktree preserved, evidence written, event recorded.\n5. E2E test: dummy-fail + checks_bypass -\u003e merge proceeds, bypass event recorded.\n6. Evidence under .ddx/executions/\u003crun-id\u003e/ shows fixture wrote result.json and ddx parsed it correctly.\n7. cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./... green; lefthook pre-commit passes.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"57ca2a85de1c0c9dd204a1daceb86eb15eaf81a1","created_at":"2026-05-02T20:51:06.107921729Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ddx-3e60fd84","depends_on_id":"ddx-aee651ec","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-05-02T20:51:09Z"}],"description":"Slice 2 of parent ddx-a946c744. Wire the checks runner (built in child slice ddx-aee651ec) into the execute-bead loop as a pre_merge gate, add the checks_bypass bead annotation with event recording, and add e2e tests.\n\nDEPENDS ON\n- ddx-aee651ec (checks protocol package + ddx ac CLI)\n\nCONTEXT\nSee parent ddx-a946c744 for full design. This slice integrates the protocol package into the merge flow and adds the bypass mechanism.\n\nSCOPE\n- cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_loop.go — call cli/internal/checks runner for all applicable checks BEFORE the merge-back step; on any status=block/error, abort merge, preserve worktree per existing iteration-preservation conventions, write evidence under .ddx/executions/\u003crun-id\u003e/, record event\n- cli/internal/bead schema — checks_bypass annotation: list of {name, reason, bead}; missing reason -\u003e bypass rejected loudly; on bypass, named check is skipped and a bypass event is recorded with the reason\n- E2E test 1: fixture .ddx/checks/dummy-fail.yaml with script that always returns status=block; ddx try on a no-op bead aborts merge, preserves worktree, evidence file present, event recorded\n- E2E test 2: same fixture + checks_bypass annotation on bead -\u003e merge proceeds, bypass event recorded\n- Tests under cli/internal/agent/ and/or cli/cmd/ following existing execute_bead_*_test.go patterns\n\nOUT OF SCOPE\n- New checks for any specific language (separate REACH-* beads)","events_attachment":"ddx-3e60fd84/events.jsonl","execute-loop-no-changes-count":1,"id":"ddx-3e60fd84","issue_type":"task","labels":["phase:2","area:agent","area:checks","kind:platform","prevention"],"notes":"Pre-merge checks gate, bypass annotation, and e2e tests are correctly implemented and well-structured. AC #7 is not strictly satisfied: commit was made with lefthook --no-verify due to a pre-existing TestReviewEvidenceApproveAttributesToTier failure, which the author documented as reproducible on base 6a64e425. Implementation packages pass green; pre-existing failure should be filed as a separate bead.","parent":"ddx-a946c744","priority":0,"session_id":"eb-9329873d","status":"closed","title":"checks integration: pre_merge hook in execute-bead loop + checks_bypass annotation + e2e","updated_at":"2026-05-03T22:24:53.47245539Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:292:{"acceptance":"- [ ] `ddx agent execute-bead` and the server/local execute-loop paths evaluate required governing execution docs before a result is merged\n- [ ] A required failing gate preserves the attempt instead of landing it, writes gate results into the execution bundle, and reports `post_run_check_failed`/equivalent preserved detail in the result surface\n- [ ] A required passing gate still allows landing and records the pass summary deterministically\n- [ ] A regression test covers both interactive execute-bead and execute-loop managed paths with required-pass and required-fail fixtures\n- [ ] Existing no-gate behavior remains mergeable and backward compatible","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"a320445041f89d66dfb5b8804d4e636edaed1f75","created_at":"2026-04-17T21:48:51.104968376Z","description":"CONTRACT-001 assigns DDx ownership of required execution semantics sufficient to decide merge vs preserve, but the shipped managed paths do not currently pass governing IDs/worktree context into gate evaluation before land. `evaluateRequiredGates()` and checks.json writing exist, but `ddx agent execute-bead` intentionally clears WtPath/GovernIDs and the server execute-loop path lands through the coordinator without invoking gate evaluation.\n\nPromote required graph-authored execution docs from dormant implementation to the actual managed-landing contract.","events_attachment":"ddx-3e7f8213/events.jsonl","execute-loop-last-detail":"agent: provider error: unexpected end of JSON input","execute-loop-last-status":"execution_failed","execute-loop-retry-after":"2026-04-18T07:18:33Z","id":"ddx-3e7f8213","issue_type":"epic","labels":["ddx","area:agent","area:exec","area:git"],"notes":"Decomposed into 3 sub-beads on 2026-04-18 after opus review. Original single-bead approach failed to converge: vidar-omlx attempt 2026-04-18T01:18 errored on provider JSON; bragi qwen3.6-35b-a3b ran 91 minutes 2026-04-18T17:34 with no land. Primitives already exist (evaluateRequiredGates, ExtractGoverningIDsFromManifest, BeadLandingResult plumbing, post_run_check_failed status). Two materially different code paths each have their own worktree-lifecycle problem, justifying split.","priority":1,"status":"closed","title":"Epic: required execution gates wired into managed execute-bead landing (both paths)","updated_at":"2026-04-19T16:56:41.62228528Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:294:{"acceptance":"Sole remaining child ddx-c7081f89 closes successfully. Then verify:\n\n1. cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./internal/server/... ./internal/agent/... passes\n2. cd /home/erik/Projects/ddx \u0026\u0026 /home/erik/.local/bin/ddx work --once --local (no flags, no pin) successfully dispatches a single-call attempt against the next ready bead; the bead's events show no kind:tier-attempt entries (default path uses single ResolveRoute call)\n3. cd /home/erik/Projects/ddx \u0026\u0026 /home/erik/.local/bin/ddx work --once --local --escalate preserves the existing tier-loop behavior (kind:tier-attempt entries appear)\n4. The bead-event taxonomy preserved on a default-path run: kind:routing fires once, kind:cost fires once, kind:execute-bead fires once for the outcome; kind:tier-attempt and kind:escalation-summary do NOT fire on the default path (they remain reserved for --escalate)","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","created_at":"2026-04-29T12:28:08.165699268Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ddx-3f406266","depends_on_id":"ddx-c7081f89","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-29T12:28:09Z"}],"description":"## Status update (filed 2026-04-29 12:50 UTC)\n\nThe bulk of this unification **already shipped** as `ddx-87fb72c2` (epic `ddx-fdd3ea36`) before this epic was filed:\n\n- `agent.routing.profile_ladders` and `agent.routing.model_overrides` are now opt-in (consulted only with `--escalate` / `--override-model`).\n- The default execute path on the CLI (`cli/cmd/agent_cmd.go`) calls `ResolveRoute` once per attempt instead of iterating a tier ladder.\n- `agent.routing.default_harness` was removed (hard error if still present).\n- `agent.ResolveTierCandidates` (from `ddx-5538aa5b`) replaced the broken literal-tier-name-as-Model pattern; tier resolution now consults the catalog.\n- See `docs/migrations/routing-config.md` for the migration the user-facing CLI surface follows.\n\n**Remaining gap (this epic now scopes only this):** the server worker path in `cli/internal/server/workers.go:650` was not updated by `ddx-87fb72c2`. It still derives `escalationEnabled := spec.Harness == \"\" \u0026\u0026 spec.Model == \"\"` instead of mirroring the CLI's `escalate \u0026\u0026 harness == \"\" \u0026\u0026 model == \"\"`. That mismatch is why `ddx work` (default mode, server-submit) still hits \"all tiers exhausted — no viable provider\" with `model_overrides` pointing at non-served models, while `ddx work --local --no-adaptive-min-tier` succeeds. Verified live in this session: `worker-20260429T033325-bedf` failed; `--no-adaptive-min-tier` got `ddx-98e6e9ef` to merge at `115b47c0` on local-tier qwen for zero cost.\n\nSole child: `ddx-c7081f89`. Once that lands, this epic closes.\n\n## Strategic direction (preserved for future reference)\n\nDDx embeds the agent SDK as a Go library to produce traceable execution units: `(bead, input_state) → (output_state, processing_metadata)`. DDx owns the execution unit and its metadata (bead events, cost ledger, escalation summary, evidence directories), and it owns operator policy (`--harness`/`--model`/`--profile`/`--max-cost`/`--no-review`/`--escalate`). It does **not** need to own provider/harness/cost/local-first routing — agent SDK already does that.\n\n| Concern | DDx (now, post-87fb72c2) | Agent SDK |\n|---|---|---|\n| Profile selection | `RouteRequest.Profile` straight to agent | `default/cheap/standard/smart/local/offline/air-gapped/fast/code-smart/code-high` |\n| Per-tier model pinning | opt-in via `--override-model` | `RouteRequest.Model` |\n| Escalation on no-provider | opt-in via `--escalate` (CLI path); **not yet on server worker path** | `escalateProfileLadder` walks `ProfileEscalationLadder=[cheap,standard,smart]` on `ErrNoLiveProvider` |\n| Cost-aware ranking | n/a (delegated) | `internal/routing/score.go` ranks by `CostClass` (local=0 wins) |\n| Adaptive success-rate gating | `escalation.AdaptiveMinTier` (sticky 50-window cheap-tier lockout, only consumed via `--escalate`) | `routing.Inputs.HistoricalSuccess map[harness]float64` |\n| Decision trace | bead events `kind:tier-attempt` per RouteCandidate | `RouteDecision.Candidates []RouteCandidate` |\n\n## Optional follow-ups (not in this epic — file separately if/when needed)\n\nThese are no longer blockers; track separately if pursued:\n\n- **Default profile = `local`** so the operator-default honors the local-LLM-first goal without an explicit `--profile local`. Currently default is `default` which maps via project config.\n- **Inject `routing.Inputs.HistoricalSuccess` per-harness** to replace `escalation.AdaptiveMinTier` with agent-native success-rate routing. Frees DDx from maintaining its own success-window state machine.\n- **Delete `cli/internal/agent/profile_ladder.go` helpers** once no caller (CLI or server) consumes them. Currently consumed only via `--escalate`; if `--escalate` is dropped or moved into agent, these can go.\n- **Delete `cli/internal/escalation/escalation.go::AdaptiveMinTier`** once the HistoricalSuccess injection above is in place.\n\n## Out of scope for this epic\n\n- Changes to agent SDK source — if a gap is found, file an upstream bead under `~/Projects/agent/.ddx/`.\n- UI/e2e work — the parent e2e drift epic `ddx-ccdf9cf9` covers that and is independent.\n- Server source changes outside `cli/internal/server/workers.go` — no API endpoint changes, no GraphQL schema changes.","events_attachment":"ddx-3f406266/events.jsonl","id":"ddx-3f406266","issue_type":"epic","labels":["area:routing","area:agent","kind:refactor","phase:build"],"notes":"REVIEW:BLOCK\n\nDiff contains only execution evidence files (manifest.json, result.json) — no source changes to cli/internal/server/workers.go or anywhere else. None of the AC items can be verified from this diff.","priority":1,"status":"closed","title":"routing-unify: delegate provider/harness/cost/local-first routing to agent SDK; ddx preserves execution-unit metadata + operator policy","updated_at":"2026-04-29T18:30:06.928832371Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:301:{"acceptance":"- [ ] New command or subcommand: `ddx doctor divergence` or `ddx divergence check` prints the divergence report\n- [ ] Thresholds are configurable via .ddx/config.yaml (default: 5 commits each side, 7 days merge-base age)\n- [ ] execute-loop refuses to start in ERROR state unless --force passed\n- [ ] Structured event 'divergence_status' emitted at loop start and on every doctor run\n- [ ] Optional webhook integration via config.yaml alert_webhook_url\n- [ ] Unit tests: each state (clean, ahead, behind, diverged, network-down, drift)\n- [ ] Integration test: run the loop on a diverged repo and observe the refuse-to-start behavior\n- [ ] Docs: README section on divergence monitoring, thresholds, and how to recover","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","created_at":"2026-04-14T12:21:10.525089812Z","description":"Fifth child of ddx-b7ee0d6f. The 14-day silent divergence on axon (eitri local 134 commits ahead of merge-base, sindri/origin 336 commits ahead) was caught only because a human happened to try pushing. A trivial monitor running a few times a day would have flagged the problem at 5 commits, not 470.\n\n## Required behavior\n\nAdd a lightweight divergence check that runs either:\n- At the top of each execute-loop iteration (cheap, ~50ms), OR\n- Periodically via a scheduled task (ddx doctor or similar), OR\n- Both\n\nThe check computes:\n- `git fetch origin \u003cbranch\u003e` (tolerant of network failure)\n- local_ahead = `git rev-list --count origin/\u003cbranch\u003e..HEAD`\n- origin_ahead = `git rev-list --count HEAD..origin/\u003cbranch\u003e`\n- merge_base_age = `git log -1 --format=%ar $(git merge-base HEAD origin/\u003cbranch\u003e)`\n\nEmit a structured event 'divergence_status' with these fields. If:\n- local_ahead \u003e threshold (default 5): warn\n- origin_ahead \u003e threshold (default 5): warn\n- both \u003e 0: ERROR — diverged, neither side is a strict ancestor\n- merge_base_age \u003e threshold (default 7 days): warn (drift)\n\nIntegration surface:\n- `ddx doctor` prints the divergence report\n- `ddx agent execute-loop` refuses to start if in the ERROR state (both sides ahead) unless --force is passed\n- An optional webhook / notification channel (config: alert_webhook_url) for ops teams\n\n## Why this is P1 not P0\n\nThe fetch/push/rebase triad (P0) prevents NEW divergence. This bead catches EXISTING divergence and alerts before it grows. Without the P0 fixes, this alert would fire constantly; with them, it should fire rarely. Still valuable as defense in depth.\n\n## Test cases\n\n- Fresh clone: report is clean (0 ahead / 0 behind)\n- Local 3 commits ahead: report shows local_ahead=3, no warning\n- Local 6 commits ahead: report shows local_ahead=6, warning emitted\n- Both sides ahead: ERROR status, execute-loop refuses to start\n- Merge base 10 days old with both sides at 0: drift warning, execute-loop continues\n- Network unreachable: report shows 'unknown', no ERROR, execute-loop continues","id":"ddx-42dd982c","issue_type":"task","labels":["execute-loop","monitoring","observability"],"parent":"ddx-b7ee0d6f","priority":1,"session_id":"eb-d16c6e3","status":"closed","title":"execute-loop: divergence monitoring and alerting","updated_at":"2026-04-14T15:56:12.030389438Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:308:{"acceptance":"- [ ] ddx bead reopen command exists\n- [ ] Status flip + notes append + event recorded atomically\n- [ ] Unit + integration tests\n- [ ] Used by the post-review path from gap #1","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-04-15T04:57:51Z","claimed-machine":"eitri","claimed-pid":"3766264","closing_commit_sha":"8e0b77a980455d4cea392d42ab4e49b01541bc95","created_at":"2026-04-15T00:49:48.573308839Z","description":"Reopening a closed bead after a failing review currently takes 3-4 separate commands: update --status open, update --notes (append), optionally update --description, optionally update --acceptance. This is error-prone and loses the atomicity guarantee that a reopen is a single logical event.\n\n## Scope\n- ddx bead reopen \u003cid\u003e [--reason \u003ctext\u003e] [--append-notes \u003ctext\u003e]\n- Atomically: set status=open, append a reopen event to the event log, optionally append notes, clear claim fields\n- Emit an event of kind=reopen that shows in ddx bead show\n- Works from CLI and from ddx agent execute-loop review-rejection path\n\n## Context\nObserved during axon ADR-018 loop: first attempt merged, opus review rejected, I had to run three ddx bead update commands plus a description rewrite to get the bead back into a ready-for-second-attempt state. An atomic reopen would have been one command.","events_attachment":"ddx-44084b3e/events.jsonl","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-04-15T05:03:51.315684175Z","id":"ddx-44084b3e","issue_type":"task","labels":["helix","area:bead","area:cli","kind:feature","gap:review-loop"],"owner":"ddx","priority":1,"session_id":"eb-40c2dece","status":"closed","title":"exec: ddx bead reopen \u003cid\u003e — atomic review-driven reopen","updated_at":"2026-04-15T05:04:15.791178942Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:314:{"acceptance":"1) TestExecuteBeadGateBlocksLanding no longer references fakeExecuteBeadGit or fakeAgentRunner. 2) Test dispatches through RealLandingGitOps + newScriptHarnessRepo (or equivalent real-git harness). 3) cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./cmd -run '^TestExecuteBeadGateBlocksLanding$' -count=1 green. 4) No other test in agent_execute_bead_test.go is modified.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-04-24T05:52:00Z","claimed-machine":"eitri","claimed-pid":"196235","closing_commit_sha":"c58c5c371e7e89be11fda93e389fc26d8dbd64b5","created_at":"2026-04-21T17:24:43.228378577Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ddx-455807e6","depends_on_id":"ddx-915240dd","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-21T17:42:24Z"}],"description":"Migrate cli/cmd/agent_execute_bead_test.go TestExecuteBeadGateBlocksLanding() from fakeExecuteBeadGit + fakeAgentRunner to real git + script harness.\n\nPattern:\n- Use cli/internal/agent/integration_helper_test.go newScriptHarnessRepo(t, beadCount) to build an isolated repo with real git.\n- Use runGitInteg (from cli/internal/git/git_basic_test.go) for any supplemental git invocations, so GIT_* env is scrubbed.\n- Replace fakeExecuteBeadGit with the RealLandingGitOps flow used in cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_land_test.go.\n- Replace fakeAgentRunner with the script harness (cli/internal/agent/script.go) driven by a per-attempt directive file. When the test needs to simulate 'agent emits no commits' or 'agent emits a dirty worktree', encode that as script directives rather than a canned Result struct.\n- Preserve every assertion — the point is that the test now exercises real git + real merge/preserve semantics, not that the surface shrinks.\n\nScope limit: ONLY this test. Do not migrate any other test in the same file; touching another test expands blast radius outside the bead.\n\nVerification: cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./cmd -run '^TestExecuteBeadGateBlocksLanding$' -count=1 passes. No struct ending in -GitOps or -Runner that fakes the thing under test is referenced from this test after the migration.\n\nGoverning concern: concerns.md §testing 'no mocks, period' + 'never mock the thing you are testing'. Parent: ddx-d9df348d.","events_attachment":"ddx-455807e6/events.jsonl","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-04-24T05:54:00.952263482Z","execute-loop-last-detail":"escalation exhausted: cancelled","execute-loop-last-status":"execution_failed","execute-loop-retry-after":"2026-04-21T23:40:43Z","id":"ddx-455807e6","issue_type":"task","labels":["phase:test","area:cli","area:agent","kind:refactor","workstream:fake-migration"],"owner":"ddx","parent":"ddx-d9df348d","priority":3,"session_id":"eb-5b3d1cdd","spec-id":"concerns.testing","status":"closed","title":"test: migrate TestExecuteBeadGateBlocksLanding to real git + script harness","updated_at":"2026-04-24T05:55:03.308131885Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:317:{"acceptance":"Go test exists, passes, and would fail if any git call-site in the agent path reverted to bare exec.Command(\"git\", ...). Test runs in under 60s.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-04-25T07:46:50Z","claimed-machine":"eitri","claimed-pid":"196235","closing_commit_sha":"931f931c6a6196af45b25f56273f30afa7945200","created_at":"2026-04-24T12:24:10.104543518Z","description":"Split from timed-out ddx-65b88ae1. Write the regression test that proves the B4+B5[a-c] migrations actually stop Bug A.\n\nTest sketch (Go test in cli/internal/agent/):\n1. Create a fake outer bare repo at /tmp/\u003ctestname\u003e/bare with 'git init --bare' and capture a copy of its config file bytes.\n2. Set GIT_DIR=\u003cbare\u003e/.git, GIT_WORK_TREE=\u003cfake-work\u003e, GIT_INDEX_FILE=\u003cfake-index\u003e in the test env via t.Setenv.\n3. Create a separate working repo in a tempdir.\n4. Construct a minimal Runner + agent.Script-based no-op harness.\n5. Drive an in-process execute-bead end-to-end hitting WorktreeAdd, SynthesizeCommit, CommitTracker, and the landing/preserve-refs path (use --no-merge preserve to exercise update-ref in the base repo without requiring a remote).\n6. Assert the fake bare repo's config bytes are byte-identical after the run. Assert no stray files appeared under \u003cbare\u003e/.git.\n\nThis is the provable gate: if Bug A is truly fixed, polluted env does not mutate the outer repo.","events_attachment":"ddx-46370e6b/events.jsonl","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-04-25T07:59:20.207110877Z","id":"ddx-46370e6b","issue_type":"task","owner":"ddx","parent":"ddx-64ac553a","priority":1,"session_id":"eb-f99106c8","status":"closed","title":"regression test: execute-bead against GIT_DIR-contaminated env leaves outer bare repo untouched","updated_at":"2026-04-25T08:00:11.084534103Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:322:{"acceptance":"1. A sub-bead for context-window gating exists and is prioritized.\n2. A sub-bead for tool-calling support gating exists.\n3. A sub-bead for effort/permissions gating exists.\n4. A sub-bead for structured-output gating exists (or a note in one of the above that it's covered incidentally).\n5. This bead closes as 'decomposed — see sub-beads'. The autorouting epic ddx-2d974641 does NOT depend on any of them for its exit gate; they are Phase 2 tracked separately.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"abeea29135139fae380daa51b3bb6df51e83395d","created_at":"2026-04-18T01:14:30.750496873Z","description":"## Problem (filed per codex + opus fresh-eyes review 2026-04-17)\n\nBoth reviews flagged the same missing concept: routing currently scores candidates on cost class, quota, and historical success rate — but does NOT gate on whether the resolved route can actually execute the requested work. Concrete failure modes this lets through:\n\n1. **Context-window overflow.** Bead prompt is 80k tokens. Fuzzy match picks a 32k-context model on the pinned provider. Routing 'succeeds'. Dispatch fails mid-stream with a provider 400 or truncated output.\n\n2. **Missing tool-calling support.** Some omlx flavors or older local servers don't implement /v1/chat/completions with tools. Routing picks them via fuzzy match. Dispatch fails with 'tools not supported' or silently returns a no-tool response that the execute-bead loop can't use.\n\n3. **Missing structured-output support.** Some provider/model combos don't implement JSON-mode / tool-use-required. If the bead prompt relies on it, routing-level blindness means the failure only surfaces at dispatch.\n\n4. **Effort / permissions.** --effort high or --permissions unrestricted may not be honored by every harness+provider combination. Routing should reject or downgrade rather than dispatch and fail.\n\nCodex: 'routing currently scores mostly on cost/quota/history, not whether a provider/model can satisfy tool calling, effort controls, permissions, or context-window needs.'\nOpus: 'If the bead prompt is 80k tokens and the fuzzy-matched model is 32k, routing succeeds and dispatch fails mid-stream. Omlx flavor may not support tools at all.'\n\n## Out of scope for this bead\n\nThis bead tracks the CONCEPT as a sibling of the main autorouting epic, but a full capability-constraint scoring system is a larger change than the current Phase-1 scope. Per opus: 'Scope this out of the epic explicitly (don't expand), but add a sibling bead so it's tracked.'\n\nSplit out into sub-scope bites is TBD:\n\n1. **Context-window gating** — smallest useful slice. RouteRequest gains an optional EstimatedPromptTokens field; evaluateCandidate rejects (or penalizes) candidates whose concrete_model's known context window is below that. Uses v0.3.11's LookupModelLimits + catalog ContextWindow fallback.\n\n2. **Tool-calling support gating** — needs per-provider / per-flavor capability metadata. Likely populated from discovery (/v1/models/status) + hand-curated capability table for harnesses.\n\n3. **Effort / permissions gating** — mostly already in place for harnesses (Harness.EffortFlag checked at routing.go:rejectIfNotViable) but provider-specific gating (e.g., 'openrouter doesn't honor effort on non-reasoning models') is not.\n\n4. **Structured-output support** — probably lowest priority; most reasoning-tool-capable models also do structured output.\n\nThis bead's AC is to file the sub-beads (smaller, focused) and close THIS bead once the sub-beads exist. The epic ddx-2d974641 does NOT depend on those sub-beads for its exit gate — context-window etc. are a Phase 2 concern. The epic is about correct resolution; capability gating is about preventing resolved-but-unrunnable routes.\n\n## Files touched (by sub-beads, not this one)\n\n- cli/internal/agent/types.go — CandidatePlan capability fields, RouteRequest capability hints\n- cli/internal/agent/routing.go — capability checks in rejectIfNotViable + scoring\n- cli/internal/agent/catalog.go — ContextWindow, supports_tools, supports_structured_output per ModelEntry/Surface","events_attachment":"ddx-4817edfd/events.jsonl","execute-loop-no-changes-count":1,"id":"ddx-4817edfd","issue_type":"task","labels":["ddx","phase:build","kind:implementation","area:agent","area:routing"],"notes":"Decomposed into sub-beads (2026-04-18, in execution worktree 20260418T064927-78e29296):\n\n- .execute-bead-wt-ddx-4817edfd-20260418T064927-78e29296-f5cec42a — context-window gating (P2)\n- .execute-bead-wt-ddx-4817edfd-20260418T064927-78e29296-854cb8a7 — tool-calling support gating (P2)\n- .execute-bead-wt-ddx-4817edfd-20260418T064927-78e29296-bb230ad5 — effort/permissions gating (P3)\n- .execute-bead-wt-ddx-4817edfd-20260418T064927-78e29296-22cadb21 — structured-output gating (P4)\n\nAll four sub-beads have parent=ddx-4817edfd. Each is prioritized per the parent description (context-window first as the smallest useful slice; structured-output last since it is likely covered incidentally by tool-calling gating). Per AC#5, the autorouting epic ddx-2d974641 does NOT depend on any of these for its exit gate; they are tracked as Phase 2 work.\n\nNote on bead IDs: the sub-beads picked up the worktree directory basename as their ID prefix instead of the conventional ddx- namespace. This is an upstream wart in `ddx bead create` ID generation when invoked from inside an execute-bead worktree (cwd basename leaks into the seq prefix). The beads themselves are correct — only the IDs are cosmetic. File a separate bead against the ddx CLI if this needs to be fixed.","parent":"ddx-2d974641","priority":2,"session_id":"eb-665c47aa","spec-id":"SD-015","status":"closed","title":"routing: pre-dispatch capability check — context window, tool support, effort, permissions","updated_at":"2026-04-18T06:56:44.667529862Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:323:{"acceptance":"library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md and .ddx/plugins/ddx/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md are rewritten to match the HELIX testing concern and the DDx concerns.md override. All of the following must be true:\n\n(1) Mechanical grep guards:\n- `grep -n \"Mock all external dependencies\" library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md` returns empty\n- `grep -n \"test doubles (mocks\" library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md` returns empty\n- `grep -n \"Use real implementations where possible\" library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md` returns empty (the integration section must use \"zero mocks, no exceptions\" not \"where possible\")\n- `grep -ciE \"stub|in-memory|extracted interface|contract test\" library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md` returns at least 10\n- `grep -c \"99%\" library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md` returns at least 1 (the \"mocks are a worst practice, avoid in 99% of cases\" phrasing is present)\n- `grep -c \"script harness\" library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md` returns at least 1\n- `grep -c \"docs/helix/01-frame/concerns.md\" library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md` returns at least 1 (cites DDx concerns)\n- `grep -c \"workflows/concerns/testing\" library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md` returns at least 1 (cites HELIX concern)\n- `grep -c \"orchTestGitOps\\|fakeExecuteBeadGit\\|gateTestGitOps\" library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md` returns at least 1 (drift signals section names the DDx-specific anti-patterns by type)\n\n(2) Structural requirements:\n- Unit Tests section explicitly states that mocks are a worst practice and names the \"extract interface, write in-memory stub, test with contract suite\" pattern as the default.\n- Integration Tests section states \"zero mocks, period, no exceptions\" and cites the script harness as the ONLY approved fake.\n- Contract Tests section contains a code block showing the \"same suite against stub + real backend\" pattern (Go-idiomatic, idiomatic for the DDx codebase).\n- New Drift Signals subsection lists at least 10 anti-patterns including testify/mock imports, gomock for first-party interfaces, per-goroutine mock git, and the named offenders in DDx's test suite.\n- The word \"mock\" appears only in prohibitions and in the Drift Signals subsection. The body of the Unit/Integration/Contract sections uses \"stub,\" \"in-memory implementation,\" or \"real backend\" exclusively.\n\n(3) Source/installed sync:\n- library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md and .ddx/plugins/ddx/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md are byte-identical after the fix.\n\n(4) Regression witness:\n- A new test fixture or smoke check somewhere in the repo (e.g., a lefthook pre-commit or a doc-validation script) greps library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md for the forbidden phrases above and fails the commit if any reappear. This prevents silent drift if someone later reverts.\n\n(5) Changelog entry or commit message:\n- The commit message explicitly references the HELIX testing concern and the DDx concerns.md override, explains why mocks are being removed from the persona, and cites at least one concrete DDx anti-pattern (orchTestGitOps / fakeExecuteBeadGit / TestConcurrentWorkersNoMergeRace) that the old persona produced.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","created_at":"2026-04-14T15:25:37.692295461Z","description":"The test-engineer-tdd persona at library/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md promotes mocks as standard practice, directly contradicting the HELIX testing concern that DDx declared active in concerns.md on 2026-04-05. Every agent that adopts this persona produces mock-heavy tests that violate the concern's rules. This is how DDx accumulated `orchTestGitOps`, `fakeExecuteBeadGit`, `gateTestGitOps`, `TestConcurrentWorkersNoMergeRace`, `mockExecutor`, and every other test-that-lies-about-its-coverage pattern the opus test plan review surfaced.\n\n## Provenance\n\n- Persona authored 2025-09-15 in commit a4cc8ac as part of FEAT-011 persona system build\n- Testing concern adopted in DDx 2026-04-05 in commit b711ac8 (`Add testing concern`)\n- The persona has been silently contradicting the concern for 9 days with no audit\n- Personas are a DDx-native concept (HELIX has no personas/ directory in workflows/); this is DDx's problem to fix\n\n## The core principle\n\n**Mocks are a worst practice and should be avoided in 99% of cases.** The right pattern, always, is: extract an interface at your domain boundary, write an in-memory stub implementation of that interface, and write a contract test suite that runs against BOTH the stub and the real backend. When both pass the same suite they are proven interchangeable. This exposes hidden assumptions, keeps stubs honest, and produces tests that assert behavior instead of call sequences.\n\nMocks — defined specifically as call-recording test doubles that assert method X was called Y times with args Z — test implementation instead of behavior. They break when internals change without user-visible consequences. They give false confidence: a passing mock test proves nothing about the system's actual behavior because the thing under test never interacts with a real dependency. Most notoriously in DDx: mock git tests have proven zero merge-race, rebase-conflict, or serialization invariants despite claiming to.\n\nThe 1% of cases where mocks are acceptable: third-party SDK boundaries where a stub is infeasible (payment processors with real-world-only callbacks, email delivery, SMS, external auth providers). Even there, prefer contract tests against a sandbox environment when one exists.\n\n## Offending sections\n\nlibrary/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md lines 90-94 (Unit Tests):\n\n```\n### Unit Tests\n- Test individual functions/methods in isolation\n- Mock all external dependencies\n- Focus on business logic\n- Use test doubles (mocks, stubs, spies)\n```\n\n`Mock all external dependencies` is absolute and wrong. The HELIX testing concern says:\n\n\u003e Prefer stubs (canned return values) over mocks (call-sequence assertions). Stubs test behavior; mocks test implementation.\n\u003e Use real implementations where practical: real databases via testcontainers or Docker Compose, real HTTP via local servers, real file systems via temp directories.\n\u003e Mock only at true system boundaries: third-party APIs, payment processors, email services, external auth providers.\n\u003e Never mock the thing you are testing.\n\n`Use test doubles (mocks, stubs, spies)` lists mocks alongside stubs as equivalent. They are not equivalent. Mocks assert call sequences (implementation detail). Stubs return canned values (behavior contract). The persona should never put them on the same line.\n\nlibrary/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md lines 96-100 (Integration Tests):\n\n```\n### Integration Tests\n- Test component interactions\n- Use real implementations where possible\n- Test database operations\n- Verify API contracts\n```\n\n`Use real implementations where possible` is weakly worded. DDx's project override in concerns.md states:\n\n\u003e Integration tests: zero mocks. No exceptions. Integration tests exercise real production implementations of every dependency in the graph — real git (t.TempDir() + scrubbed GIT_* env), real filesystem, real bead store, real coordinator, real server, real agent harness (the script harness is the only approved fake for the AI-provider boundary, and it does not mock — it performs real filesystem and git operations deterministically). A test that substitutes any mock for a production component is not an integration test. It is a unit test that is lying about its coverage.\n\nThe persona must echo this in absolute language, not \"where possible.\"\n\n## What to change\n\n### Rewrite the Unit Tests section\n\nReplace lines 90-94 with guidance that matches the HELIX concern and DDx override exactly. Required content:\n\n- The code under test depends on interfaces at domain boundaries. Extract the interface if it does not exist.\n- Isolate the code under test with in-memory STUB implementations of those interfaces. Stubs return canned values the test sets up. They never record call sequences.\n- Every stub must be backed by a contract test suite that the real implementation ALSO passes. Same suite, both implementations. That proves they are interchangeable.\n- Never use testify/mock, gomock, mockery-generated interfaces for assertion purposes, or any call-sequence assertion library. Assert on behavior — what did the code do to observable state? — not on call counts.\n- Never mock git, filesystem, bead store, database, queue, or any first-party infrastructure — use real implementations in temp directories.\n- The only approved \"fake\" in DDx unit tests is an in-memory implementation of a first-party interface you own.\n- Mocks are a worst practice. Avoid them in 99% of cases in favor of extracted interfaces with in-memory stubs. The 1% exception is third-party SDK boundaries where a stub is infeasible.\n\n### Rewrite the Integration Tests section\n\nReplace lines 96-100 with:\n\n- Integration tests use zero mocks. Period. No exceptions.\n- Real database in a temp dir, real filesystem via t.TempDir(), real git via git init in a temp dir with scrubbed GIT_* env, real HTTP via a local test server, real queues, real bead store, real coordinator, real server.\n- The only approved fake in the DDx suite is the `script` harness (cli/internal/agent/script.go) as the AI-provider boundary replacement. It is not a mock — it performs real filesystem and git operations deterministically against the worktree.\n- A test that substitutes any mock for a production component is not an integration test. It is a unit test that is lying about its coverage.\n- Never mock the thing you are testing. A coordinator test that substitutes a fake LandingGitOps is mocking the thing under test; use RealLandingGitOps against a real git repo.\n\n### Add a Contract Tests section\n\nThe persona currently has a Contract Tests section at lines 102-106. Rewrite it to cover the \"stub must pass the real implementation's contract suite\" pattern, not just \"APIs meet specifications.\" Example structure:\n\n```go\n// contract_test.go — runs the same suite against both implementations\nfunc TestBeadStoreContract(t *testing.T) {\n    cases := []struct {\n        name  string\n        build func(t *testing.T) Store\n    }{\n        {\"memory\", func(t *testing.T) Store { return NewMemoryStore() }},\n        {\"file\",   func(t *testing.T) Store { return NewFileStore(t.TempDir()) }},\n    }\n    for _, c := range cases {\n        t.Run(c.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n            s := c.build(t)\n            t.Run(\"CreateAndGet\", func(t *testing.T) { /* ... */ })\n            t.Run(\"UpdateLosesNoFields\", func(t *testing.T) { /* ... */ })\n            t.Run(\"ConcurrentWritersSerialized\", func(t *testing.T) { /* ... */ })\n        })\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIf the stub passes and the real backend fails, the backend is broken or the stub is lying. Either way the contract suite exposes the drift immediately. This is how DDx keeps stubs honest.\n\n### Add a Drift Signals subsection\n\nMirror the HELIX testing concern's drift signals and add DDx-specific anti-patterns. Any agent reviewing code that contains these should reject or refactor:\n\n- `testify/mock` imports in new test files\n- `gomock` generated mocks for first-party interfaces\n- Structs named `*Mock*`, `fake*Git`, `fake*Store`, `orchTest*GitOps`, `gateTest*GitOps` that implement a first-party interface for assertion purposes (in-memory stubs for first-party interfaces are OK and encouraged, as long as they are real implementations, not call recorders)\n- Per-goroutine mock git in concurrency tests (the shared-writer invariant is not being tested)\n- test.skip, .skip(), @Ignore, @Disabled without a linked issue\n- Mock-heavy tests that assert call order rather than observable state\n- Static JSON fixture files (use factory functions with fakers instead)\n- Tests named `test1`, `testHelper`, `it works` (rename to describe behavior)\n- `expect(true).toBe(true)` or tautological assertions\n- Commented-out tests (git has the history; delete them)\n- Retry loop around a flaky test (fix the flake)\n\n### Add citations to authoritative sources\n\nThe persona must explicitly cite:\n\n- **HELIX testing concern**: `workflows/concerns/testing/concern.md` in HELIX (or `.ddx/plugins/helix/workflows/concerns/testing/concern.md` when installed) — the upstream authority for the stubs-over-mocks rule.\n- **DDx concerns.md**: `docs/helix/01-frame/concerns.md` — the DDx-specific application of the rule, including the zero-mocks-in-integration-tests override.\n- **Script harness**: `cli/internal/agent/script.go` — the canonical deterministic fake agent.\n- **Integration test reference**: `cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_integration_test.go` — the reference pattern that every new integration test should follow.\n\n### Update the installed copy\n\nlibrary/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md is the source of truth. The installed copy at .ddx/plugins/ddx/personas/test-engineer-tdd.md must also be updated so downstream projects (HELIX and others) that depend on the DDx plugin pick up the fix. Either (a) update both files in the same commit and let the install process pick up the new source the next time it runs, or (b) run the library sync mechanism as part of the bead work.\n\n## Why this matters\n\nEvery test in DDx's history that was written by an agent following this persona produced mock-heavy code. Those tests passed CI, appeared to cover invariants, and silently proved nothing. The alpha14 → alpha16 session has been the first time anyone audited them end-to-end and discovered the drift. Without this fix, the next agent adopting the persona will reproduce the same broken pattern.\n\nThe cost of fixing the persona is hours. The cost of NOT fixing it is weeks of debugging \"why doesn't the land coordinator work\" when the real answer is \"because every test that 'proved' the old merge path worked was a lie.\"","id":"ddx-482fad2f","issue_type":"bug","labels":["area:library","area:docs","area:testing","kind:correctness"],"priority":1,"session_id":"eb-51e0142","status":"closed","title":"test-engineer-tdd persona contradicts testing concern (promotes mocks)","updated_at":"2026-04-14T15:43:14.958570875Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:325:{"acceptance":"1) TestExecuteBeadTimeoutNoCommitsReportsExecutionFailure no longer references fakeExecuteBeadGit or fakeAgentRunner. 2) Test dispatches through RealLandingGitOps + newScriptHarnessRepo (or equivalent real-git harness). 3) cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./cmd -run '^TestExecuteBeadTimeoutNoCommitsReportsExecutionFailure$' -count=1 green. 4) No other test in agent_execute_bead_test.go is modified.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","claimed-at":"2026-04-24T04:54:14Z","claimed-machine":"eitri","claimed-pid":"196235","closing_commit_sha":"2256459db6ccc5749bc8a930eaa833448d074e7e","created_at":"2026-04-21T17:24:42.402437361Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ddx-49383ded","depends_on_id":"ddx-915240dd","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-21T17:42:24Z"}],"description":"Migrate cli/cmd/agent_execute_bead_test.go TestExecuteBeadTimeoutNoCommitsReportsExecutionFailure() from fakeExecuteBeadGit + fakeAgentRunner to real git + script harness.\n\nPattern:\n- Use cli/internal/agent/integration_helper_test.go newScriptHarnessRepo(t, beadCount) to build an isolated repo with real git.\n- Use runGitInteg (from cli/internal/git/git_basic_test.go) for any supplemental git invocations, so GIT_* env is scrubbed.\n- Replace fakeExecuteBeadGit with the RealLandingGitOps flow used in cli/internal/agent/execute_bead_land_test.go.\n- Replace fakeAgentRunner with the script harness (cli/internal/agent/script.go) driven by a per-attempt directive file. When the test needs to simulate 'agent emits no commits' or 'agent emits a dirty worktree', encode that as script directives rather than a canned Result struct.\n- Preserve every assertion — the point is that the test now exercises real git + real merge/preserve semantics, not that the surface shrinks.\n\nScope limit: ONLY this test. Do not migrate any other test in the same file; touching another test expands blast radius outside the bead.\n\nVerification: cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./cmd -run '^TestExecuteBeadTimeoutNoCommitsReportsExecutionFailure$' -count=1 passes. No struct ending in -GitOps or -Runner that fakes the thing under test is referenced from this test after the migration.\n\nGoverning concern: concerns.md §testing 'no mocks, period' + 'never mock the thing you are testing'. Parent: ddx-d9df348d.","events_attachment":"ddx-49383ded/events.jsonl","execute-loop-heartbeat-at":"2026-04-24T04:57:44.647284303Z","execute-loop-last-detail":"escalation exhausted: no_changes","execute-loop-last-status":"no_changes","execute-loop-no-changes-count":1,"execute-loop-retry-after":"2026-04-21T23:32:56Z","id":"ddx-49383ded","issue_type":"task","labels":["phase:test","area:cli","area:agent","kind:refactor","workstream:fake-migration"],"owner":"ddx","parent":"ddx-d9df348d","priority":3,"session_id":"eb-2c68e6b7","spec-id":"concerns.testing","status":"closed","title":"test: migrate TestExecuteBeadTimeoutNoCommitsReportsExecutionFailure to real git + script harness","updated_at":"2026-04-24T04:58:35.137000443Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:332:{"acceptance":"1. Production root command execution uses a SIGINT/SIGTERM-backed context and calls ExecuteContext.\n2. First signal prints exactly `Cancel received, shutting down gracefully` once, visible to the operator.\n3. Second signal hard-aborts or restores default signal behavior; the behavior is documented in a source comment and covered by a focused test where practical.\n4. TestRootSignal_FirstInterruptCancelsContextAndPrintsGracefulMessage verifies cancellation and exact message without relying on slow real-time sleeps.\n5. TestRootSignal_MessagePrintedOnce verifies repeated first-path cancellation does not duplicate the message.\n6. Existing command tests that use ExecuteContext continue to control cancellation explicitly.\n7. `cd cli \u0026\u0026 go test ./cmd/... -run \"TestRootSignal|TestWork|TestTry|TestExecuteLoop\" -count=1` passes.\n8. `lefthook run pre-commit` passes.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"799c60228eff72de5ffb5eae650f8c24eedefd29","created_at":"2026-05-06T15:17:21.686303893Z","description":"PROBLEM\nCtrl-C / SIGTERM should trigger DDx cooperative cancellation for `ddx work` and `ddx try`, but the CLI root currently executes without a signal-backed context. Operators see abrupt termination rather than an explicit shutdown message and cleanup path.\n\nROOT CAUSE WITH FILE:LINE\n- cli/main.go:31 calls `cmd.Execute(workingDir)` and relies on the default process signal behavior.\n- cli/cmd/root.go:31-39 initializes the root command and calls `rootCmd.Execute()` instead of `ExecuteContext(ctx)`.\n- cli/cmd/work.go:37-40 advertises `signal` as a stop condition, but no production signal handler cancels `cmd.Context()`.\n- docs/helix/01-frame/features/FEAT-010-task-execution.md:423-434 and docs/helix/02-design/solution-designs/SD-025-task-execution-lifecycle.md:177-190 require first-signal cooperative shutdown and the exact operator message `Cancel received, shutting down gracefully`.\n\nPROPOSED FIX\n- Install a root SIGINT/SIGTERM handler for production CLI execution using `signal.NotifyContext` or equivalent.\n- Execute Cobra with the signal-backed context.\n- On first signal, print `Cancel received, shutting down gracefully` exactly once to the operator-visible stream before cancellation-dependent cleanup begins.\n- On a second signal, hard-abort or restore default signal behavior so wedged cleanup can still be killed.\n- Keep tests deterministic by exposing a small helper/seam rather than sending real OS signals where unit tests can use a cancellable context.\n\nNON-SCOPE\n- Do not decide bead cleanup policy here beyond propagating context cancellation.\n- Do not change server worker stop/watchdog behavior.","events_attachment":"ddx-4ab66676/events.jsonl","execute-loop-no-changes-count":1,"id":"ddx-4ab66676","issue_type":"task","labels":["phase:2","area:cli","area:agent","kind:bug","reliability","spec:FEAT-010","spec:SD-025","interrupt"],"parent":"ddx-99a3be32","priority":0,"session_id":"eb-a98d5682","spec-id":"FEAT-010","status":"closed","title":"cli: translate SIGINT/SIGTERM into graceful ddx cancellation","updated_at":"2026-05-06T16:35:07.334965994Z"}
.ddx/beads-archive.jsonl:334:{"acceptance":"The epic stays open indefinitely as a backlog for cost-tiered execution and measurement work. Closes ONLY if DDx pivots away from this optimization goal entirely (unlikely). Progress is measured by: (a) count of child beads closed that concretely improved the ladder, reviewed-rejection rate, or measurement granularity; (b) observable reduction in cost-per-closed-bead over time once the metric exists; (c) observable reduction in opus-review rejection rate as the cheap-tier work improves.","archived_at":"2026-05-07T04:29:14Z","closing_commit_sha":"c4518bd8b520a204440559044aeecaa799fcf414","created_at":"2026-04-15T03:47:42.980708133Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"ddx-4b59b816","depends_on_id":"ddx-e7254128","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-20T13:58:09Z"},{"issue_id":"ddx-4b59b816","depends_on_id":"ddx-7bc0c8d5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-20T14:36:21Z"}],"description":"Standing optimization goal captured 2026-04-15: get the most work done for the least cost, and continuously improve our ability to measure and tune that trade-off.\n\n## Operating principles\n\n1. Cheap models do the work. Local (vidar-coder / qwen3-coder-next / other LM Studio hosts), then budget-tier cloud (claude haiku / gpt-5.4-mini), then standard (claude sonnet / gpt-5.4), then smart (claude opus / gpt-5.4 high-effort). Start cheap; escalate on failure.\n2. Strong models review. Every closed bead gets an opus review against its acceptance. Rejected reviews reopen with specific fixes.\n3. Deterministic fixes are the top rung of the ladder. When LLMs keep failing on a mechanical task, apply the fix manually; capture as input for routing policy.\n4. Measurement feeds optimization. Track per-bead which model attempted, how long, whether it passed review, what failure mode if any.\n\n## Existing bead tie-ins (helix review-loop epic from parallel agent)\n\n- ddx-a317208c exec: post-merge review agent on-by-default in execute-loop\n- ddx-dc231144 exec: tier-based auto-escalation driven by resource discovery\n- ddx-fdf031c9 exec: ddx bead review \u003cid\u003e — template a review prompt\n- ddx-44084b3e exec: ddx bead reopen \u003cid\u003e — atomic review-driven reopen\n- ddx-518b2690 exec: ddx agent run --output text — plain result extraction\n\n## Existing bead tie-ins (mine)\n\n- ddx-bd0691fe Epic: surface ddx-agent routing visibility (providers/models/check/route-status commands — prereq for routing policy)\n- ddx-bfc1aeaf Visibility 8: capture routing decisions in bead evidence (kind:routing) — feeds the measurement database\n\n## New child beads (to be filed under this epic)\n\nThe beads below are scope for this epic. File as children when we are ready to work each one. NOT pre-filed to avoid blocking the current Svelte+GraphQL migration.\n\n1. Per-bead cost aggregation: extend bead evidence schema to record tokens-in/tokens-out/cost-usd per attempt; add ddx bead metrics aggregate command that rolls up per-bead totals.\n2. Ladder success-rate analytics: ddx agent metrics tier-success — query last N closed beads, report success rate at each tier (vidar-coder, claude-sonnet, claude-opus, deterministic-fix).\n3. Prompt-context pre-filter: shrink the prompt for cheap-tier attempts — omit the full plan doc and include only the bead description + acceptance + 2 most relevant files.\n4. Failure-mode taxonomy: document the known failure modes (vidar long-context hang, read-loop stall, ship-unbuilt-code, opus-shape-miss, etc.) as bead evidence kinds so measurement can aggregate by mode.\n5. Review-rejection telemetry: aggregate opus-review outcomes (APPROVE / APPROVE_WITH_EDITS / REJECT) per originating tier so we know where the shape gaps are.\n6. Dashboard page for the metrics (requires Svelte migration Stage 4 to land first).\n\n## Why this is captured as an epic not a memory-only goal\n\nMemory is read; epics are tracked. Future sessions should see this in ddx bead list and be able to file child beads against it as we discover new measurement needs or optimization opportunities. The memory file is the principle; this epic is the backlog.","events_attachment":"ddx-4b59b816/events.jsonl","execute-loop-no-changes-count":1,"id":"ddx-4b59b816","issue_type":"epic","labels":["ddx","phase:build","kind:optimization","area:agent","area:cli","area:measurement","goal:throughput-per-dollar","wave:deferred","workstream:agent-upgrade"],"priority":2,"session_id":"eb-2dcc8231","status":"closed","title":"Epic: cost-tiered execution + measurement — maximize closed-bead throughput per dollar","updated_at":"2026-04-28T22:37:12.898039753Z"}
